causes'),(11474,230,21,'left',0,'Statistics','500 grams of cocaine can get you the same 5-year prison sentence as only 5 grams of crack80% of American offenders end up back in prison4,300,000 violent crimes were reportedly committed against US residents age 12 or older in 20091,000,000 Americans are in jail or awaiting trial60% is the estimated unemployment rate for American ex-offenders one year after release','500 grams of cocaine can get you the same 5-year prison sentence as only 5 grams of crack<br/>80% of American offenders end up back in prison<br/>4,300,000 violent crimes were reportedly committed against US residents age 12 or older in 2009<br/>1,000,000 Americans are in jail or awaiting trial<br/>60% is the estimated unemployment rate for American ex-offenders one year after release'),(11475,231,21,'left',0,'Statistics','76,000,000 women in developing countries experience unintended pregnancies each year and 19 million resort to unsafe abortions38 women undergo an unsafe abortions every minute1 women dies every 8 minutes due to a botched abortion2,700,000 infant deaths could be prevented each year through accessibility to contraceptives','76,000,000 women in developing countries experience unintended pregnancies each year and 19 million resort to unsafe abortions<br/>38 women undergo an unsafe abortions every minute<br/>1 women dies every 8 minutes due to a botched abortion<br/>2,700,000 infant deaths could be prevented each year through accessibility to contraceptives'),(11476,232,21,'left',0,'Statistics','3:00-6:00pm on school days is the prime time for violent juvenile crime3 times more likely to skip classes, use marijuana, or engage in sexual activity without an after school activity15,000,000 kids  have no place to go after school','3:00-6:00pm on school days is the prime time for violent juvenile crime<br/>3 times more likely to skip classes, use marijuana, or engage in sexual activity without an after school activity<br/>15,000,000 kids  have no place to go after school'),(11477,233,21,'left',0,'Statistics','50% increase expected in water withdrawals by 2025 in developing countries; 18 percent in developed countries1 in 3 people on every continent in the world are affected by water scarcity2,000 to 5,000 iltres of water is the amount of water required to produce one person\'s daily food','<p>50% increase expected in water withdrawals by 2025 in developing countries; 18 percent in developed countries<br />1 in 3 people on every continent in the world are affected by water scarcity<br />2,000 to 5,000 iltres of water is the amount of water required to produce one person\'s daily food</p>'),(11478,234,21,'left',0,'Statistics','10% point test score difference from having a top quartile teacher rather than a bottom quartile teacher3,700,000 teachers in the US currently','10% point test score difference from having a top quartile teacher rather than a bottom quartile teacher<br/>3,700,000 teachers in the US currently'),(11479,235,21,'left',0,'Statistics','90% of teachers and 86% of parents connect physical activity with improved academic performance and behavior300% increase in the past 25 years in the number of children aged 6-11 who are overweight75% of US children are not active 20 minutes a day','90% of teachers and 86% of parents connect physical activity with improved academic performance and behavior<br/>300% increase in the past 25 years in the number of children aged 6-11 who are overweight<br/>75% of US children are not active 20 minutes a day'),(11480,236,21,'left',0,'Statistics','12% of the world\'s land is designated as some type of protected area3,000,000 new acres of land are destroyed by development every year in the US','12% of the world\'s land is designated as some type of protected area<br/>3,000,000 new acres of land are destroyed by development every year in the US'),(11481,237,21,'left',0,'Statistics','$2,700,000,000 people in the world have no access to formal financial services160,000,000 people in developing countries are served by microfinance','$2,700,000,000 people in the world have no access to formal financial services<br/>160,000,000 people in developing countries are served by microfinance'),(11482,238,21,'left',0,'Statistics','1,000,000 premature deaths each year are linked to urban air pollution1,000,000,000 people are exposed to outdoor air pollution annually','1,000,000 premature deaths each year are linked to urban air pollution<br/>1,000,000,000 people are exposed to outdoor air pollution annually'),(11483,239,21,'left',0,'Statistics','40% of countries provide girls and boys equal access to education2/3 of the world\'s 880,000,000 illiterate adults are women','40% of countries provide girls and boys equal access to education<br/>2/3 of the world\'s 880,000,000 illiterate adults are women'),(11484,240,21,'left',0,'Statistics','95% of all  abortions are chosen as a method of birth control.5% of all  abortions are performed as a result of sexual crimes, health problems, or fetal abnormality','95% of all  abortions are chosen as a method of birth control.<br/>5% of all  abortions are performed as a result of sexual crimes, health problems, or fetal abnormality'),(11485,241,21,'left',0,'Statistics','50% of the  six million pregnancies in the US each year are unintended8 murders, 17  attempted murders, and 416 death threats against abortion providers in the US and Canada have been carried out since 197787% of all US  counties have no identifiable abortion provider, as a result, women must travel long distances to reach the nearest provider','50% of the  six million pregnancies in the US each year are unintended<br/>8 murders, 17  attempted murders, and 416 death threats against abortion providers in the US and Canada have been carried out since 1977<br/>87% of all US  counties have no identifiable abortion provider, as a result, women must travel long distances to reach the nearest provider'),(11486,242,21,'left',0,'Statistics','In 1988, more than 125 countries in the world were polio-endemic. Today, only four  countries are polio-endemic.The remaining polio-endemic countries are Afghanistan, India, Nigeria and PakistanOne in 200 infections leads to irreversible paralysis (usually in the legs)','In 1988, more than 125 countries in the world were polio-endemic. <br/>Today, only four  countries are polio-endemic.<br/>The remaining polio-endemic countries are Afghanistan, India, Nigeria and Pakistan<br/>One in 200 infections leads to irreversible paralysis (usually in the legs)'),(28538,4303,27,'center',1,'What does New York Asian Women\'s Center do? ','New York Asian Women\'s Center helps immigrant, low-income women and children from abusive environments transition to independent lives. Domestic violence is particularly difficult for Asian immigrant women because of their limited English proficiency, cultural taboos associated with escaping abuse, fear and misunderstanding of their legal rights, and economic dependency on their abusive husbands.&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n\r\n3 out of 4 NYAWC clients have been physically assaulted, while others have been terrorized by threats, stalking, and other forms of psychological abuse\r\n80% of the women NYAWC serves have annual incomes of $15,000 or less\r\n85% of the women NYAWC serves have a primary language other than English. &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNYAWC offers comprehensive, culturally competent support in order to help women overcome these challenges. ﻿','<p>New York Asian Women\'s Center helps immigrant, low-income women and children from abusive environments transition to independent lives. Domestic violence is particularly difficult for Asian immigrant women because of their limited English proficiency, cultural taboos associated with escaping abuse, fear and misunderstanding of their legal rights, and economic dependency on their abusive husbands.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>3 out of 4 NYAWC clients have been physically assaulted, while others have been terrorized by threats, stalking, and other forms of psychological abuse</li>\r\n<li>80% of the women NYAWC serves have annual incomes of $15,000 or less</li>\r\n<li>85% of the women NYAWC serves have a primary language other than English. &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>NYAWC offers comprehensive, culturally competent support in order to help women overcome these challenges. ﻿</p>'),(28539,4303,27,'center',2,'How are they doing it?','NYAWC works both as a direct service and an advocacy organization. As a direct service organization, NYAWC provides women with everything from counseling to case management to legal support.&nbsp; NYAWC also runs a confidential, 24-hour hotline for women in need of emergency interpretation, referrals, or counseling services. The hotline employs counselors who speak over a dozen Asian languages and dialects.   &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\nIn addition, NYAWC provides emergency housing for women and children in need. After leaving NYAWC\'s emergency housing, women are able to participate in continuing care programs.   &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\nAs an advocacy organization, NYAWC educates communities about the realities of domestic violence and advocates for clients within the legal system. Through their initiative \"Project Free: Ending Modern-day Slavery,\" they raise awareness of human trafficking among Asian American communities, law enforcement and other service providers, while directly supporting survivors of human trafficking.         ﻿','<p>NYAWC works both as a direct service and an advocacy organization. As a direct service organization, NYAWC provides women with everything from counseling to case management to legal support.&nbsp; <br /><br />NYAWC also runs a confidential, 24-hour hotline for women in need of emergency interpretation, referrals, or counseling services. The hotline employs counselors who speak over a dozen Asian languages and dialects.   &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In addition, NYAWC provides emergency housing for women and children in need. After leaving NYAWC\'s emergency housing, women are able to participate in continuing care programs.   &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As an advocacy organization, NYAWC educates communities about the realities of domestic violence and advocates for clients within the legal system. Through their initiative \"Project Free: Ending Modern-day Slavery,\" they raise awareness of human trafficking among Asian American communities, law enforcement and other service providers, while directly supporting survivors of human trafficking.         ﻿</p>'),(28540,4303,27,'left',0,'Key Programs/Initiatives','\r\n24-Hour Multilingual Hotline\r\nCrisis Intervention and Counseling\r\nEmergency Residential Program\r\nChildren&rsquo;s support groups and counseling\r\nProject Free: Ending Modern-Day Slavery\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li>24-Hour Multilingual Hotline</li>\r\n<li>Crisis Intervention and Counseling</li>\r\n<li>Emergency Residential Program</li>\r\n<li>Children&rsquo;s support groups and counseling</li>\r\n<li>Project Free: Ending Modern-Day Slavery</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28544,9,21,'left',0,'Statistics','\r\nObesity is one of the leading causes of preventable death in the world.\r\n17% of children in the US age 2-19 are obese, this number is triple the rate it was 30 years ago.\r\n$147,000,000,000 is spent annually on obesity-related diseases.\r\nTwo thirds, or more than 190,000,000, Americans are obese.\r\nThere has been a 30% increase in the amount of sweetener intake in the past 40 years.\r\n55% of Diabetes Type 2 patients are obese when diagnosed.\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li>Obesity is one of the <strong>leading causes of preventable death</strong> in the world.</li>\r\n<li><strong>17% of children in the US</strong> age 2-19 are obese, this number is triple the rate it was 30 years ago.</li>\r\n<li><strong>$147,000,000,000</strong> is spent annually on obesity-related diseases.</li>\r\n<li>Two thirds, or <strong>more than 190,000,000</strong>, Americans are obese.</li>\r\n<li>There has been a <strong>30% increase</strong> in the amount of sweetener intake in the past 40 years.</li>\r\n<li><strong>55% of Diabetes Type 2 </strong>patients are obese when diagnosed.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28553,193,21,'left',0,'Statistics','\r\nMalaria causes 1,000,000 deaths per year.\r\nThere are 300,000,000 to 500,000,000 cases worldwide per year.\r\nMalaria causes 2.23% of deaths worldwide.\r\n3,300,000,000 people in 106 countries are at risk of malaria.\r\n\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li>Malaria causes <strong>1,000,000 deaths</strong> per year.</li>\r\n<li>There are <strong>300,000,000 to 500,000,000 cases</strong> worldwide per year.</li>\r\n<li>Malaria causes <strong>2.23% of deaths</strong> worldwide.</li>\r\n<li><strong>3,300,000,000 people</strong> in 106 countries are at risk of malaria.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--EndFragment-->'),(28585,10180,27,'center',1,'What does Human RIghts Watch do?','Human Rights Watch (HRW) is an independent organization that brings attention to oppressed individuals around the world. They believe that objectively reporting on human rights violations influences powerful leaders and stakeholders, ultimately preventing further abuses from happening and ensuring human rights abusers are brought to justice.','<p>Human Rights Watch (HRW) is an independent organization that brings attention to oppressed individuals around the world. They believe that objectively reporting on human rights violations influences powerful leaders and stakeholders, ultimately preventing further abuses from happening and ensuring human rights abusers are brought to justice.</p>'),(28586,10180,27,'center',2,'How are they doing it?','Human Rights Watch researchers work in the field to investigate human rights conditions around the world. Their first-hand, in-depth research incorporates interviews with victims of abuse, eyewitnesses, and other key stakeholders.  After they complete a report, HRW meets with the governments and businesses that are involved, applying pressure to hold abusers accountable and to change harmful policies.&nbsp;  They also raise public awareness about the atrocities that they investigate. Their studies provide up-to-date information across a range of human rights topics and their reports are often cited in the press, as well as government and United Nations findings.','<p>Human Rights Watch researchers work in the field to investigate human rights conditions around the world. Their first-hand, in-depth research incorporates interviews with victims of abuse, eyewitnesses, and other key stakeholders. <br /><br /> After they complete a report, HRW meets with the governments and businesses that are involved, applying pressure to hold abusers accountable and to change harmful policies.&nbsp; <br /><br /> They also raise public awareness about the atrocities that they investigate. Their studies provide up-to-date information across a range of <a href=\"http://www.hrw.org/en/topics\">human rights topics</a> and their reports are often cited in the press, as well as government and United Nations findings.</p>'),(28587,10180,27,'center',3,'What have they achieved?','Evidence of impact includes:\r\n\r\nInternational Labor Organization created a legally binding convention that strengthens and enforces laws protecting domestic workers; HRW was closely involved in every step of treaty negotiations (2011). \r\nThe Indian government orders that their border security guards be issued non-lethal weapons and that disciplinary action be taken against perpetrators of abuses, just weeks after HRW reported on the excessive use of lethal force (2011). \r\nBarrick Gold, the world\'s largest gold mining company, has taken steps to end abuse in gold mines in Papua New Guinea, including the arrest of security guards accused of gang rape and other crimes;&nbsp; these steps were brought on by HRW\'s findings (2011). \r\n\r\nMore success stories are available on their website.\r\nScope of work includes:\r\n\r\nPublishes more than 100 reports and briefings each year\r\nCovers over 90 countries around the world     ﻿\r\n','<p>Evidence of impact includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>International Labor Organization created a legally binding convention that strengthens and enforces laws protecting domestic workers; HRW was closely involved in every step of treaty negotiations (2011). </li>\r\n<li>The Indian government orders that their border security guards be issued non-lethal weapons and that disciplinary action be taken against perpetrators of abuses, just weeks after HRW reported on the excessive use of lethal force (2011). </li>\r\n<li>Barrick Gold, the world\'s largest gold mining company, has taken steps to end abuse in gold mines in Papua New Guinea, including the arrest of security guards accused of gang rape and other crimes;&nbsp; these steps were brought on by HRW\'s findings (2011). </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>More <a href=\"http://www.hrw.org/about/success-stories\">success stories are available on their website</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Scope of work includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Publishes more than 100 reports and briefings each year</li>\r\n<li>Covers over 90 countries around the world     ﻿</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28588,10180,27,'center',4,'Founder\'s Story','Helsinki Watch was formed in 1978 to support citizen groups throughout the Soviet bloc that monitored government compliance with the 1975 Helsinki Accords. By pushing out alerts of abusive government action to the media-a \"naming and shaming\" approach-Helsinki Watch raised international awareness and contributed to the Eastern European democratic uprisings in the late 1980s. Ten years later, after regional groups like Americas Watch, Asia Watch, Africa Watch, and Middle East Watch formed, the groups officially adopted an inclusive name-Human Rights Watch. ﻿','<p>Helsinki Watch was formed in 1978 to support citizen groups throughout the Soviet bloc that monitored government compliance with the 1975 Helsinki Accords. By pushing out alerts of abusive government action to the media-a \"naming and shaming\" approach-Helsinki Watch raised international awareness and contributed to the Eastern European democratic uprisings in the late 1980s. Ten years later, after regional groups like Americas Watch, Asia Watch, Africa Watch, and Middle East Watch formed, the groups officially adopted an inclusive name-Human Rights Watch.<br /><br /> ﻿</p>'),(28599,4303,27,'center',3,'What have they achieved?','Evidence of impact includes:\r\n\r\n91% of the women NYAWC serves do not return to live with their abusers.\r\nClients report decreases in all forms of abuse, including      psychological abuse.\r\nUpon exiting the program, the majority of clients report an      increase in social supports, such as friends, co-workers, and social      services professionals. \r\nUpon exiting the program, one-third of clients report an      increase in income. \r\n\r\n\r\nScope of work includes:\r\n\r\nAssists more than 600 abused women and their children each year\r\nOperates two Emergency Residences with a total capacity of 40 beds\r\nReceives 3,000 calls each year to their hotline\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','<p><em>Evidence of impact includes:</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>91% of the women NYAWC serves do not return to live with their abusers.</li>\r\n<li>Clients report decreases in all forms of abuse, including      psychological abuse.</li>\r\n<li>Upon exiting the program, the majority of clients report an      increase in social supports, such as friends, co-workers, and social      services professionals. </li>\r\n<li>Upon exiting the program, one-third of clients report an      increase in income. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p><em>Scope of work includes:</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Assists more than 600 abused women and their children each year</li>\r\n<li>Operates two Emergency Residences with a total capacity of 40 beds</li>\r\n<li>Receives 3,000 calls each year to their hotline</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(28601,3691,27,'center',2,'How do they do it?','Polaris\' comprehensive approach to stopping human trafficking includes:\r\n\r\nClient Case Management: Polaris staff members are on call 24/7 to assist victims of human trafficking. Social services from group therapy to transitional housing are offered to all clients.\r\nPublic Policy Advocacy: Through grassroots outreach and advocacy, Polaris works to advance federal and state-level laws that address the needs of trafficking survivors as seek accountability for traffickers. Polaris has worked with dozens of states to draft key legislation that sets a precedent to eradicate human trafficking.   &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\nTraining and Technical Assistance: Polaris works to provide key community advocates, coalitions, and task forces with comprehensive information on trends in human trafficking, state and federal laws, and best practices. &nbsp;Through this work, Polaris aims to help institutionalize practices used to combat human trafficking.   &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\nNational Human Trafficking Hotline: Callers to the hotline can report a tip, request emergency services, or request anti-trafficking information. It is anonymous and open 24-hours a day.   &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\nPublic Communications:&nbsp; Polaris uses mass communication, social media, and targeted campaigns to raise awareness about human trafficking and to apply pressure against entities that support or enable human trafficking.&nbsp; They also work to teach community members and at-risk youth populations about human-trafficking signs and victim identification.   &nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThey have also begun work internationally, supporting other countries to develop similar programs.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ﻿','<p>Polaris\' comprehensive approach to stopping human trafficking includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Client Case Management: </strong>Polaris staff members are on call 24/7 to assist victims of human trafficking. Social services from group therapy to transitional housing are offered to all clients.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Public Policy Advocacy: </strong>Through grassroots outreach and advocacy, Polaris works to advance federal and state-level laws that address the needs of trafficking survivors as seek accountability for traffickers. Polaris has worked with dozens of states to draft key legislation that sets a precedent to eradicate human trafficking.   &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><strong>Training and Technical Assistance: </strong>Polaris works to provide key community advocates, coalitions, and task forces with comprehensive information on trends in human trafficking, state and federal laws, and best practices. &nbsp;Through this work, Polaris aims to help institutionalize practices used to combat human trafficking.   &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><strong>National Human Trafficking Hotline: </strong>Callers to the hotline can report a tip, request emergency services, or request anti-trafficking information. It is anonymous and open 24-hours a day.   &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><strong>Public Communications:&nbsp; </strong>Polaris uses mass communication, social media, and targeted campaigns to raise awareness about human trafficking and to apply pressure against entities that support or enable human trafficking.&nbsp; They also work to teach community members and at-risk youth populations about human-trafficking signs and victim identification.   &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>They have also begun work internationally, supporting other countries to develop similar programs.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong></strong> ﻿</p>'),(28602,3691,27,'center',3,'What have they achieved?','Evidence of their impact includes:\r\n\r\nCo-founded the federally funded DC Human Trafficking Task Force, which has rescued over 90 victims and successfully prosecuted over 45 traffickers\r\nThrough National Human Trafficking Resource Center, responded to more than 7,500 calls that identified nearly 1,000 potential victims of human trafficking (2009) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\r\n\r\nScope of their work includes:\r\n\r\nTrained 9,488 individuals in the U.S. and 2,780 individuals in Japan on human trafficking, focused on informing law enforcement, government officials, and other service providers on what they need to know to effectively support anti-trafficking efforts&nbsp;         ﻿\r\n','<p>Evidence of their impact includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Co-founded the federally funded DC Human Trafficking Task Force, which has rescued over 90 victims and successfully prosecuted over 45 traffickers</li>\r\n<li>Through National Human Trafficking Resource Center, responded to more than 7,500 calls that identified nearly 1,000 potential victims of human trafficking (2009) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Scope of their work includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Trained 9,488 individuals in the U.S. and 2,780 individuals in Japan on human trafficking, focused on informing law enforcement, government officials, and other service providers on what they need to know to effectively support anti-trafficking efforts&nbsp;         ﻿</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28603,3691,27,'center',1,'What does Polaris Project do?','Polaris works to end human trafficking by raising public awareness, advocating for public policy, training those in the field (e.g., law enforcement), and providing direct support to the survivors of human trafficking.&nbsp;','<p>Polaris works to end human trafficking by raising public awareness, advocating for public policy, training those in the field (e.g., law enforcement), and providing direct support to the survivors of human trafficking.&nbsp;</p>'),(28604,6448,27,'center',2,'How do they do it?','The Restavek Freedom Foundation supports children living as restaveks and advocates for the end of current restavek practices by:\r\n\r\nSupporting and advocating for children living as restaveks: Staff work as child advocates, providing emotional support to children in the program. They meet with these children regularly to monitor their physical condition and emotional well being, advocating for their needs when necessary. When they find children who are in extremely abusive situations, they work to move them to safety.The staff works with host families to ensure restaveks in the program can go to school, and they keep in contact with their teachers and school directors. Restavek Freedom Foundation also provides uniforms, books, and school fees to enable these children to go to school. &nbsp; &nbsp;\r\nWorking with host families: Restavek Freedom Foundation establishes a relationship with host families and their communities in order to influence change in their treatment of restaveks. The staff teaches literacy skills to host parents; this provides staff with an opportunity to speak with them about human rights and the treatment of children. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\r\nRaising global awareness on child slavery: Restavek Freedom Foundation raises awareness on child slavery in Haiti by working with schools, churches, community organizations and universities. They also educate the public through their website and newsletter, sharing information about the issue and how others can help.&nbsp;&nbsp;        ﻿\r\n','<p>The Restavek Freedom Foundation supports children living as restaveks and advocates for the end of current restavek practices by:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Supporting and advocating for children living as restaveks: </strong>Staff work as child advocates, providing emotional support to children in the program. They meet with these children regularly to monitor their physical condition and emotional well being, advocating for their needs when necessary. When they find children who are in extremely abusive situations, they work to move them to safety.<br /><br />The staff works with host families to ensure restaveks in the program can go to school, and they keep in contact with their teachers and school directors. Restavek Freedom Foundation also provides uniforms, books, and school fees to enable these children to go to school. &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><strong>Working with host families:</strong> Restavek Freedom Foundation establishes a relationship with host families and their communities in order to influence change in their treatment of restaveks. The staff teaches literacy skills to host parents; this provides staff with an opportunity to speak with them about human rights and the treatment of children. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><strong>Raising global awareness on child slavery: </strong>Restavek Freedom Foundation raises awareness on child slavery in Haiti by working with schools, churches, community organizations and universities. They also educate the public through their website and newsletter, sharing information about the issue and how others can help.&nbsp;&nbsp;        ﻿</li>\r\n</ol>'),(28605,6448,27,'center',3,'What have they achieved? ','Scope of work includes:\r\n\r\nDirectly supports more than 400 children (2009)\r\nNational conference on child      slavery was attended by over 500 Haitian leaders (2009)\r\n','<p>Scope of work includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Directly supports more than 400 children (2009)</li>\r\n<li>National conference on child      slavery was attended by over 500 Haitian leaders (2009)</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28616,140,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','Food security is defined as the state of having physical and economic access to sufficient and nutritious food, without fluctuations or shortages season to season and year to year. There are currently over 900 million people living around the world in a chronic state of hunger, with another 2 billion who are food insecure, intermittently lacking access to food. It is estimated that 17,000 children a day - 6 million a year - die from hunger.\r\nAccording to the United Nations World Food Programme, hunger and malnutrition represent the number one health risk worldwide. Hunger and malnutrition set off a vicious cycle of poverty, preventing people from being physically and mentally active enough to work and provide for themselves and their families. Hunger compromises immune systems and leaves individuals more vulnerable to disease. Hungry children are often malnourished since pregnancy, inheriting a lifetime of compromised health.\r\nWho It Impacts\r\n\r\n98 percent of the 900 million hungry are in the developing world.\r\nThree quarters of the hungry live in rural villages, mostly in Asia and Africa.\r\n25 percent of all hungry people are children.\r\n\r\nCauses\r\n\r\nNatural disasters are a major source of food insecurity throughout the developing world, with droughts being the most common cause of food shortage.\r\nWar and violent conflicts interrupt food supply, with food blockades often wielded as a weapon.\r\nPoverty leaves many without the resources to purchase seeds and land to raise crops and become self-sustained.\r\nLack of agricultural infrastructure in developing countries leaves communities without the basic tools and technologies to farm.\r\nEnvironmental degradation in developing countries makes land and water unusable for producing food.\r\nPopulation growth and resource trends lead to intermittent food crises in the developing world. The growing world population, spikes in oil prices, diversion of corn for ethanol production, speculative stockpiling, and foreign land grabs within developing countries tip already fragile food systems into crisis.\r\n','<p>Food security is defined as the state of having physical and economic access to sufficient and nutritious food, without fluctuations or shortages season to season and year to year. There are currently over 900 million people living around the world in a chronic state of hunger, with another 2 billion who are food insecure, intermittently lacking access to food. It is estimated that 17,000 children a day - 6 million a year - die from hunger.</p>\r\n<p>According to the United Nations World Food Programme, hunger and malnutrition represent the <strong>number one health risk worldwide</strong>. Hunger and malnutrition set off a vicious cycle of poverty, preventing people from being physically and mentally active enough to work and provide for themselves and their families. Hunger compromises immune systems and leaves individuals more vulnerable to disease. Hungry children are often malnourished since pregnancy, inheriting a lifetime of compromised health.</p>\r\n<p><em>Who It Impacts</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>98 percent of the 900 million hungry are in the <strong>developing world</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Three quarters of the hungry live in <strong>rural villages, mostly in Asia and Africa.</strong></li>\r\n<li>25 percent of all hungry people are <strong>children</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>Causes</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Natural disasters</strong> are a major source of food insecurity throughout the developing world, with droughts being the most common cause of food shortage.</li>\r\n<li><strong>War and violent conflicts</strong> interrupt food supply, with food blockades often wielded as a weapon.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Poverty</strong> leaves many without the resources to purchase seeds and land to raise crops and become self-sustained.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Lack of agricultural infrastructure</strong> in developing countries leaves communities without the basic tools and technologies to farm.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Environmental degradation</strong> in developing countries makes land and water unusable for producing food.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Population growth and resource trends</strong> lead to intermittent food crises in the developing world. The growing world population, spikes in oil prices, diversion of corn for ethanol production, speculative stockpiling, and foreign land grabs within developing countries tip already fragile food systems into crisis.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28617,140,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Non-governmental and multilateral organizations currently address food crises and insecurity through both short-term emergency food aid and longer-term agricultural, market, trade and policy development. Most agree that a balance of both is essential for long-term success-while emergencies require immediate relief and aid, solely relying on food aid can disrupt local markets and lower prices in recipient countries.Non-governmental organizations like Oxfam International, World Vision, Care, Mercy Corps, Catholic Relief Services engage in direct food aid as well as development programs designed to help families employ sustainable small-scale farming using organic fertilizers and drip irrigation techniques.The United Nations World Food Programme (UNWFP) is currently the largest humanitarian agency addressing hunger, and does so primarily through direct food aid, cash transfers, and food vouchers. The UNWFP also supports local agriculture in developing countries by purchasing food directly from small farmers, incentivizing them to produce surplus crops and enter agricultural markets. Through its Special Programme for Food Security, the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization helps to formulate and replicate successful food security programs and practices in developing countries on a national scale. It advises on rural infrastructure, agricultural practices, and low-cost technology implementation.The United States Agency for International Development (USAID) is the chief arm of the U.S. government tasked with addressing hunger, malnutrition, and food security issues in developing countries. It does so through a mix of emergency relief and programs designed to promote economic growth, agricultural productivity, and market and trade expansion.Recent Developments:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nFrom 1970 to 1997, the number of hungry and malnourished people worldwide was declining. But since then, the number has been increasing.\r\nThe 2008 food crisis, sparked by a sharp spike in global food prices, brought renewed attention to food security, sparking the United nations Secretary-general to appoint a&nbsp;high level task force&nbsp;to the matter, and the World Bank to form the&nbsp;Global Food Crisis Response Program&nbsp;(GFRP).\r\nIn July 2011&nbsp;Reuters reported&nbsp;that African land grabs by rich countries looking to secure their own food supply poses a rising threat to food security in Africa.\r\n','<p>Non-governmental and multilateral organizations currently address food crises and insecurity through both short-term emergency food aid and longer-term agricultural, market, trade and policy development. Most agree that a balance of both is essential for long-term success-while emergencies require immediate relief and aid, solely relying on food aid can disrupt local markets and lower prices in recipient countries.<br /><br />Non-governmental organizations like Oxfam International, World Vision, Care, Mercy Corps, Catholic Relief Services engage in direct food aid as well as development programs designed to help families employ sustainable small-scale farming using organic fertilizers and drip irrigation techniques.<br /><br />The United Nations World Food Programme (UNWFP) is currently the largest humanitarian agency addressing hunger, and does so primarily through direct food aid, cash transfers, and food vouchers. The UNWFP also supports local agriculture in developing countries by purchasing food directly from small farmers, incentivizing them to produce surplus crops and enter agricultural markets. Through its Special Programme for Food Security, the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization helps to formulate and replicate successful food security programs and practices in developing countries on a national scale. It advises on rural infrastructure, agricultural practices, and low-cost technology implementation.<br /><br />The United States Agency for International Development (USAID) is the chief arm of the U.S. government tasked with addressing hunger, malnutrition, and food security issues in developing countries. It does so through a mix of emergency relief and programs designed to promote economic growth, agricultural productivity, and market and trade expansion.<br /><br /><br /><em>Recent Developments:<br /></em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<em>&nbsp;</em>\r\n<li>From 1970 to 1997, the number of hungry and malnourished people worldwide was declining. But since then, the number has been increasing.</li>\r\n<li>The 2008 food crisis, sparked by a sharp spike in global food prices, brought renewed attention to food security, sparking the United nations Secretary-general to appoint a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.un.org/issues/food/taskforce/background.shtml\">high level task force</a>&nbsp;to the matter, and the World Bank to form the<a href=\"http://www.worldbank.org/foodcrisis/\">&nbsp;Global Food Crisis Response Program</a>&nbsp;(GFRP).</li>\r\n<li>In July 2011&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/26/us-investment-land-idUSTRE76P77P20110726\">Reuters reported</a>&nbsp;that African land grabs by rich countries looking to secure their own food supply poses a rising threat to food security in Africa.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28622,140,21,'center',2,'Further Reading ','\r\nUSAID: Food Security\r\nUnited Nations World Food Programme: Hunger\r\nWorld Health Organization: Food Security\r\nFood and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO): Food security: concepts and measurement\r\n\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source: World Food Programme','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/agriculture/food_security.htm\">USAID: Food Security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.wfp.org/hunger\">United Nations World Food Programme: Hunger</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.who.int/trade/glossary/story028/en/\">World Health Organization: Food Security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.fao.org/docrep/005/y4671e/y4671e06.htm\">Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO): Food security: concepts and measurement</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br />\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source: World Food Programme</em></p>'),(28623,201,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','Today nearly 1 billion people lack access to clean drinking water, and over 2.5 billion lack access to sanitation. Lack of water sanitation is the leading cause of infection in the world; contaminated water in the developing world is a major contributor to diarrheal disease-the second leading cause of death worldwide. According to the United Nations, 10% of global disease could be alleviated by improving access to clean water. Geographical Impact\r\n\r\nLack of access to clean water is a pervasive problem throughout much of the developing world. The crisis is particularly acute in Central America, Africa, and Southern Asia.\r\n\r\nPopulation impact\r\n\r\nThe clean water crisis takes a particular toll on women and children, not only in terms of health but also in terms of education and economic opportunity. The burden of finding and transporting clean water often falls on women and children, who must travel miles for hours daily in order to obtain clean water for their families.\r\n Water-related illnesses in developing countries overwhelm and cripple already fragile public health systems. \r\n Water-related illnesses in wage earners are responsible for tremendous losses in productivity and have an overwhelming impact on the GDP of developing countries.\r\n Children are often denied access to schools that do not have clean and separate sanitation facilities.\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n','<p>Today nearly 1 billion people lack access to clean drinking water, and over 2.5 billion lack access to sanitation. Lack of water sanitation is the leading cause of infection in the world; contaminated water in the developing world is a major contributor to diarrheal disease-the second leading cause of death worldwide. According to the United Nations, 10% of global disease could be alleviated by improving access to clean water.<br /><em><br /> <em>Geographical Impact</em><br /></em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lack of access to clean water is a <strong>pervasive problem throughout much of the developing world</strong>. The crisis is particularly acute in <strong>Central America, Africa, and Southern Asia</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em><em>Population impact</em><br /></em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The clean water crisis takes a particular toll on <strong>women and children</strong>, not only in terms of health but also in terms of <strong>education and economic opportunity</strong>. The burden of finding and transporting clean water often falls on women and children, who must travel miles for hours daily in order to obtain clean water for their families.</li>\r\n<li> Water-related illnesses in developing countries <strong>overwhelm and cripple already fragile public health systems</strong>. </li>\r\n<li> Water-related illnesses in wage earners are responsible for tremendous <strong>losses in productivity</strong> and have an overwhelming impact on the GDP of developing countries.</li>\r\n<li> Children are often <strong>denied access to schools</strong> that do not have clean and separate sanitation facilities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<em> </em> \r\n</ul>'),(28624,201,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Efforts to combat the clean water crisis most often come in the form of direct infrastructure projects in impacted communities throughout the developing world. Non-governmental organizations engage in direct field work by funding and overseeing the building of wells and sanitation systems for communities that lack adequate facilities and access. A major challenge is the prolonged upkeep of wells and sanitation systems once a project is completed and an organization leaves a community. Organizations must provide direction and training to communities for maintaining and fixing wells. Other non-infrastructure approaches include providing portable chlorine dispensers that sanitize water at the point of collection, and basic household water treatment and storage education. Prominent U.S. organizations that sponsor development projects include Water.org, Charity:Water, Water for the People, and Global Water Challenge. Funding for projects comes from a mix of corporate and non-corporate foundation grants and grassroots member donations. The United Nations Children\'s Fund (UNICEF) includes water and sanitation as one of its major areas of focus, coordinating and overseeing infrastructure projects while relying on UN member nations for sponsorship and funding. ﻿Recent Developments: \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nIn 2000, all United Nations member organizations agreed to a set of eight Millennium Development Goals to achieve by 2015; halving the number of people without access to clean drinking water and sanitation is one of these eight goals.\r\nAccording to a 2010 report by the World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF, at the current rate of progress the world will miss the sanitation target by almost 1 billion people. Even if the target were met, 1.7 billion people would still be without access.\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\nAccording to the same report, 84 percent of people living in developing countries now have access to cleaner drinking water from safer sources, indicating that this specific target will be met or exceeded.','<p>Efforts to combat the clean water crisis most often come in the form of direct infrastructure projects in impacted communities throughout the developing world. Non-governmental organizations engage in direct field work by funding and overseeing the building of wells and sanitation systems for communities that lack adequate facilities and access. A major challenge is the prolonged upkeep of wells and sanitation systems once a project is completed and an organization leaves a community. Organizations must provide direction and training to communities for maintaining and fixing wells.<br /><br /> Other non-infrastructure approaches include providing portable chlorine dispensers that sanitize water at the point of collection, and basic household water treatment and storage education.<br /><br /> Prominent U.S. organizations that sponsor development projects include Water.org, Charity:Water, Water for the People, and Global Water Challenge. Funding for projects comes from a mix of corporate and non-corporate foundation grants and grassroots member donations.<br /><br /> The United Nations Children\'s Fund (UNICEF) includes water and sanitation as one of its major areas of focus, coordinating and overseeing infrastructure projects while relying on UN member nations for sponsorship and funding.<br /><br /> ﻿<em>Recent Developments:<br /> </em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<em> </em> \r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In 2000, all United Nations member organizations agreed to a set of eight Millennium Development Goals to achieve by 2015; halving the number of people without access to clean drinking water and sanitation is one of these eight goals.</p>\r\n<p>According to a 2010 report by the World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF, at the current rate of progress the world will miss the sanitation target by almost 1 billion people. Even if the target were met, 1.7 billion people would still be without access.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em> </em></p>\r\n<p>According to the same report, 84 percent of people living in developing countries now have access to cleaner drinking water from safer sources, indicating that this specific target will be met or exceeded.</p>'),(28625,201,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nUNICEF: Water, Sanitation, Hygiene\r\nWorld Health Organization: Water\r\nWorld Health Organization: Sanitation\r\nWater.org: Facts\r\ncharity:water video:&nbsp;Water Changes Everything\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nProfile Photo Source: Water.org','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.unicef.org/wash/index.html\">UNICEF: Water, Sanitation, Hygiene</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.who.int/topics/water/en/\">World Health Organization: Water</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.who.int/topics/sanitation/en/\">World Health Organization: Sanitation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://water.org/learn-about-the-water-crisis/facts/\">Water.org: Facts</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.charitywater.org/whywater/\">charity:water video:&nbsp;Water Changes Everything</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source: Water.org</em></p>'),(28626,201,21,'left',1,'Organizations Working on this Issue','\r\ncharity:water\r\nwater.org\r\nPopulation Services International\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"/charitywater_\">charity:water</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/waterorg\">water.org</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/populationservicesinternational\">Population Services International</a></li>\r\n</ul>'),(28627,140,21,'left',1,'Organizations Working on this Issue','\r\nWorld Food Programme\r\nCommunity Food Security Coalition\r\nThe Food Trust\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"/worldfoodprogramme\">World Food Programme</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/communityfoodsecuritycoalition\">Community Food Security Coalition</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/thefoodtrust\">The Food Trust</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(28628,166,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','AIDS is a disease caused by the HIV virus. Left untreated, HIV leads to a progressive failure of the immune system, allowing life-threatening infections and cancers to debilitate and ultimately kill an infected person. The majority of HIV infections throughout the world today are caused by unprotected sexual intercourse between men and women.In 2009, the World Health Organization estimated that 33.3 million people were living with HIV, with 2.6 million new infections and 1.8 million AIDS deaths that year.Geographical ImpactWhile the HIV/AIDS pandemic is a global phenomenon and is not restricted to any particular region, certain regions are disproportionately impacted and are the focus of global prevention and treatment.\r\n\r\nSub-Saharan Africa is by far the hardest-hit region and is the greatest focus of global efforts. In 2007, sub-Saharan Africa contained over 60% of the world&rsquo;s HIV-infected individuals, and over 70% of all AIDS deaths. In some countries, 1 in 5 adults is infected with HIV. The pandemic impacts every aspect of social and civil society in the region, severely limiting economic development and perpetuating poverty and political unrest.\r\nEastern Europe and Central Asia currently represent the only regions where HIV infection rates are rising. According to UNAIDS, the number of people living with HIV infections has almost tripled since 2000, numbering 1.4 million in 2009.\r\nThe United States is estimated to have over a million people living with HIV, and nearly half a million diagnosed with AIDS. In the U.S., African Americans account for the largest proportion of those living with AIDS. AIDS has killed over half a million Americans since discovery of the disease.\r\n\r\nPopulation Impact \r\n\r\n \r\nWomen&nbsp;make up slightly over half of the 30 million adults living with HIV infections globally. HIV/AIDS is the leading cause of death among women of reproductive age worldwide. Women are more vulnerable to sexual transmission of HIV &ndash; women are twice as likely as men to become infected through unprotected sex.\r\nChildren make up 2.5 million of the people living with HIV around the world. 9 in 10 children infected with HIV contract it from their mother during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\r\nYoung adults&nbsp;comprise a disproportionate percentage of those living with HIV due to it being a sexually transmitted disease. Young adults and adolescents comprise more than a third of all new infections globally, and half of all new infections in the United States.\r\n','<p>AIDS is a disease caused by the HIV virus. Left untreated, HIV leads to a progressive failure of the immune system, allowing life-threatening infections and cancers to debilitate and ultimately kill an infected person. The majority of HIV infections throughout the world today are caused by unprotected sexual intercourse between men and women.<br /><br />In 2009, the World Health Organization estimated that 33.3 million people were living with HIV, with 2.6 million new infections and 1.8 million AIDS deaths that year.<br /><br /><em>Geographical Impact<br /></em>While the HIV/AIDS pandemic is a global phenomenon and is not restricted to any particular region, certain regions are disproportionately impacted and are the focus of global prevention and treatment.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Sub-Saharan Africa</strong> is by far the hardest-hit region and is the greatest focus of global efforts. In 2007, sub-Saharan Africa contained over 60% of the world&rsquo;s HIV-infected individuals, and over 70% of all AIDS deaths. In some countries, 1 in 5 adults is infected with HIV. The pandemic impacts every aspect of social and civil society in the region, severely limiting economic development and perpetuating poverty and political unrest.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Eastern Europe and Central Asia</strong> currently represent the only regions where HIV infection rates are rising. According to UNAIDS, the number of people living with HIV infections has almost tripled since 2000, numbering 1.4 million in 2009.</li>\r\n<li><strong>The United States</strong> is estimated to have over a million people living with HIV, and nearly half a million diagnosed with AIDS. In the U.S., African Americans account for the largest proportion of those living with AIDS. AIDS has killed over half a million Americans since discovery of the disease.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><em>Population Impact<br /> </em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<em> </em>\r\n<li><strong>Women&nbsp;</strong>make up slightly over half of the 30 million adults living with HIV infections globally. HIV/AIDS is the leading cause of death among women of reproductive age worldwide. Women are more vulnerable to sexual transmission of HIV &ndash; women are twice as likely as men to become infected through unprotected sex.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Children</strong> make up 2.5 million of the people living with HIV around the world. 9 in 10 children infected with HIV contract it from their mother during pregnancy or breastfeeding.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Young adults&nbsp;</strong>comprise a disproportionate percentage of those living with HIV due to it being a sexually transmitted disease. Young adults and adolescents comprise more than a third of all new infections globally, and half of all new infections in the United States.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28630,166,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','The leading strategy for prevention of HIV infection in adults and adolescents, in terms of success and cost effectiveness, is condom promotion and distribution. The majority of efforts to prevent HIV infections in children focus on prevention of transmission from mother to child. Antiretroviral drugs &ndash; the primary class of drugs used to combat the HIV virus &ndash; must be made available to mothers during pregnancy and labor in order to prevent transmission of the virus to a newborn, and mothers must also avoid breastfeeding. Prevention of AIDS-related deaths relies on making available antiretroviral drugs that keep those infected with HIV from developing AIDS.Funding for these efforts comes from national governments, private foundations, and multilateral organizations, of which the largest is the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria. While they don&rsquo;t provide funding, the World Health Organization (WHO) and the Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) are the leading international organizations involved in coordinating, monitoring, and evaluating efforts worldwide.Recent Developments\r\n\r\nAccording to a 2010 UNAIDS report, the global AIDS epidemic has begun to stabilize, with new infections peaking in the late 1990s and now declining. AIDS-related deaths are also declining significantly due to the wider availability and use of antiretroviral drugs.\r\nIn May of 2011, an international study found that antiretroviral drugs might play a major role in not only treating HIV-infected individuals but also in preventing new infections in those not already infected.\r\n','<p>The leading strategy for prevention of HIV infection in adults and adolescents, in terms of success and cost effectiveness, is condom promotion and distribution. The majority of efforts to prevent HIV infections in children focus on prevention of transmission from mother to child. Antiretroviral drugs &ndash; the primary class of drugs used to combat the HIV virus &ndash; must be made available to mothers during pregnancy and labor in order to prevent transmission of the virus to a newborn, and mothers must also avoid breastfeeding. Prevention of AIDS-related deaths relies on making available antiretroviral drugs that keep those infected with HIV from developing AIDS.<br /><br />Funding for these efforts comes from national governments, private foundations, and multilateral organizations, of which the largest is the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria. While they don&rsquo;t provide funding, the World Health Organization (WHO) and the Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) are the leading international organizations involved in coordinating, monitoring, and evaluating efforts worldwide.<br /><br /><em>Recent Developments</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>According to a 2010 UNAIDS report, the global AIDS epidemic has begun to stabilize, with new infections peaking in the late 1990s and now declining. AIDS-related deaths are also declining significantly due to the wider availability and use of antiretroviral drugs.</li>\r\n<li>In May of 2011, an international study found that antiretroviral drugs might play a major role in not only treating HIV-infected individuals but also in preventing new infections in those not already infected.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28631,166,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nJoint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS)\r\nCDC Factsheets on HIV/AIDS\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source: Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.unaids.org/en/resources/presscentre/factsheets/\">Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/hiv/resources/factsheets/\">CDC Factsheets on HIV/AIDS</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source: Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation</em></p>'),(28636,166,21,'left',1,'Organizations Working on this Issue','\r\nElizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation&nbsp;\r\nPopulation Action International&nbsp;\r\nGHESKIO\r\nThe Global Fund\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"/elizabethglaserpediatricaidsfoundation\">Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/populationactioninternational_\">Population Action International&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/gheskio\">GHESKIO</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/theglobalfund\">The Global Fund</a></li>\r\n</ul>'),(28639,12601,27,'center',0,'What does DOC2DOCK do?','\r\nAcross the developing world, medical centers are facing inventory shortages due to limited resources and unreliable infrastructure. Meanwhile, U.S. hospitals waste thousands of tons of medical supplies every day. U.S. government regulations require any unused supplies in opened outer packages to be destroyed, even if they are wrapped in individual, sterile packages.\r\nDOC2DOCK collects those supplies and redistributes them around the world, particularly in developing African countries as well as post-disaster areas like Haiti.\r\n','<p><!--StartFragment--></p>\r\n<p>Across the developing world, medical centers are facing inventory shortages due to limited resources and unreliable infrastructure. Meanwhile, U.S. hospitals waste thousands of tons of medical supplies every day. U.S. government regulations require any unused supplies in opened outer packages to be destroyed, even if they are wrapped in individual, sterile packages.</p>\r\n<p>DOC2DOCK collects those supplies and redistributes them around the world, particularly in developing African countries as well as post-disaster areas like Haiti.</p>\r\n<!--EndFragment-->'),(28640,12601,27,'center',1,'How do they do it?','DOC2DOCK collects supplies and equipment from hospitals in the United States. A team of volunteers inspects and tests all supplies and equipment. Through assessements by local hospitals in developing countries, DOC2DOCK finds out which supplies are in the most demand. After matching needed supplies to hospitals, DOC2DOCK ships 40-foot containers across the world. Each container can carry $500,000 worth of supplies and equipment, and with shipping costs on reaching $25,000 per container, the organization is able to ensure the shipment of $20 worth of supplies for every dollar donated.&nbsp;\r\nDOC2DOCK has formed partnerships with local organizations to ensure the delivery of supplies and equipment to the right place. They proudly note that every container they\'ve shipped has reached its destination.         ﻿','<p>DOC2DOCK collects supplies and equipment from hospitals in the United States. A team of volunteers inspects and tests all supplies and equipment. Through assessements by local hospitals in developing countries, DOC2DOCK finds out which supplies are in the most demand.<br /><br /> After matching needed supplies to hospitals, DOC2DOCK ships 40-foot containers across the world. Each container can carry $500,000 worth of supplies and equipment, and with shipping costs on reaching $25,000 per container, the organization is able to ensure the shipment of $20 worth of supplies for every dollar donated.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>DOC2DOCK has formed partnerships with local organizations to ensure the delivery of supplies and equipment to the right place. They proudly note that every container they\'ve shipped has reached its destination.         ﻿</p>'),(28641,12601,27,'center',2,'What have they achieved? ','﻿Scope of work includes:\r\n\r\nHas shipped 25 containers to hospitals in      Africa and Haiti\r\nHave provided supplies that have helped care for more than 2      million people\r\nDelivered nearly 1,400 pounds of medical      supplies (including antibiotics, analgesics, pediatric crutches, and      infant formula) to Haiti following the massive earthquake in 2010\r\nSent a \"mammovan,\" a mobile mammography van,      to Kaplala, Uganda, allowing residents of the area to be screened for      breast cancer\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','<p>﻿Scope of work includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Has shipped 25 containers to hospitals in      Africa and Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Have provided supplies that have helped care for more than 2      million people</li>\r\n<li>Delivered nearly 1,400 pounds of medical      supplies (including antibiotics, analgesics, pediatric crutches, and      infant formula) to Haiti following the massive earthquake in 2010</li>\r\n<li>Sent a \"mammovan,\" a mobile mammography van,      to Kaplala, Uganda, allowing residents of the area to be screened for      breast cancer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(28655,5577,27,'center',1,'How do they do it?','﻿350.org organizes volunteers and activists across the globe in innovative ways. They use the internet to unite people in different countries and cultures, facilitating their participation in synchronized, large-scale demonstrations. Examples of their work include:\r\n\r\nInternational Day of Climate Action: On October 24, 2009, activists encouraged      delegates of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change to      push for policies that would lower carbon emissions. Over 5,200      synchronized demonstrations took place in 181 different countries, ranging      from marches, walks, home retrofittings, tree plantings, and gigantic      depictions of the number \"350.\" CNN called the multinational event the      \"most widespread day of political action in the planet\'s history.\"&nbsp; Video available here.\r\n350 EARTH, a global art project: Citizens and artists across      the world created massive art installations to show the impact of climate      change; each installation was large enough to be seen from space.&nbsp; Video available here.\r\n10/10/10 Global Work Party: 350.org joined with the      10:10 campaign to organize a global day of action filled with over 7,000      events in 188 countries; the activities ranged from public demonstrations      to solar panel installations.&nbsp; Video available here.\r\n','<p>﻿350.org organizes volunteers and activists across the globe in innovative ways. They use the internet to unite people in different countries and cultures, facilitating their participation in synchronized, large-scale demonstrations.<br /><br /> Examples of their work include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>International Day of Climate Action</strong>: On October 24, 2009, activists encouraged      delegates of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change to      push for policies that would lower carbon emissions. Over 5,200      synchronized demonstrations took place in 181 different countries, ranging      from marches, walks, home retrofittings, tree plantings, and gigantic      depictions of the number \"350.\" CNN called the multinational event the      \"most widespread day of political action in the planet\'s history.\"&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=noPcVKf24rk\">Video available here</a>.</li>\r\n<li><strong><a href=\"http://earth.350.org/\">350 EARTH</a>, a global art project: </strong>Citizens and artists across      the world created massive art installations to show the impact of climate      change; each installation was large enough to be seen from space.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0-HnrMrQ6Tw\">Video available here</a>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>10/10/10 Global Work Party</strong>: 350.org joined with the      10:10 campaign to organize a global day of action filled with over 7,000      events in 188 countries; the activities ranged from public demonstrations      to solar panel installations.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-PoOkvz6v8\">Video available here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28656,5577,27,'center',2,'What have they achieved? ','Scope of work includes:\r\n\r\nThousands of volunteer organizers in over 188      countries\r\n\r\nA recap of 2010\'s campaigns is available on their website.&nbsp;&nbsp;         ﻿\r\n&nbsp;','<p>Scope of work includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Thousands of volunteer organizers in over 188      countries</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />A <a href=\"http://www.350.org/2010/index.html\">recap of 2010\'s campaigns</a> is available on their website.&nbsp;&nbsp;         ﻿</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(28657,5577,27,'center',3,'Founder\'s story:','\r\nAuthor Bill McKibben published The End of Nature in 1989; the text is considered to be the first book concerning climate change to be written for a general audience. Nearly 20 years later, McKibben teamed up with a team of university friends and colleagues to found Step It Up in 2007, a campaign that organized over 2,000 rallies at iconic landmarks in the United States. Step It Up\'s goal was to urge Congress to cut carbon emissions by 80% by 2050.&nbsp;\r\nRecognizing a need to encourage political leaders across the world to take action against deadly levels of carbon in the earth\'s atmosphere, the Step It Up team decided to take its model and extend it into a global context. Through 350.org, the team has motivated activists throughout the world to find creative ways to inspire change and find a solution to the climate crisis.&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','<p><!--StartFragment--></p>\r\n<p>Author Bill McKibben published <em>The End of Nature</em> in 1989; the text is considered to be the first book concerning climate change to be written for a general audience. Nearly 20 years later, McKibben teamed up with a team of university friends and colleagues to found Step It Up in 2007, a campaign that organized over 2,000 rallies at iconic landmarks in the United States. Step It Up\'s goal was to urge Congress to cut carbon emissions by 80% by 2050.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Recognizing a need to encourage political leaders across the world to take action against deadly levels of carbon in the earth\'s atmosphere, the Step It Up team decided to take its model and extend it into a global context. Through 350.org, the team has motivated activists throughout the world to find creative ways to inspire change and find a solution to the climate crisis.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!--EndFragment-->\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(28658,219,21,'center',0,'What it is the problem?','Each year, 25 million animals are used in the United States for experiments, 10 billion land animals are processed for food, 30 million are killed for fur, up to 75 million dogs and 85 million cats are kept as pets, and hundreds of thousands of wild and domestic animals are used for human entertainment.In all, the commercial and domestic use of animals by humans presents a situation that is ripe for animal mistreatment and suffering.The primary settings and issues that animal welfare and protection efforts address include:\r\n\r\nDomestic neglect and abuse - While direct abuse of animals is certainly a problem in many households, neglect through inadequate feeding, shelter, and general care is a less noticeable but much more prevalent form of domestic animal cruelty.\r\nAnimal shelter euthanasia - Pet abandonment, as well as general overpopulation of pets that results from irresponsible breeding, low adoption rates, and lack of spaying and neutering, leads to overcrowding in shelters. Over half of all dogs and cats entering shelters are eventually euthanized.\r\nUse in entertainment - Dogfights, cockfights and other cruel sports are the most visible forms of animal cruelty in entertainment. But settings such as circuses, zoos, races, transportation, and even TV and film are opportunities where animals may be mistreated and abused.\r\nExperiments and testing - Animals are routinely used to conduct scientific research or to test the safety of cosmetics, chemicals and other products. Critics claim that in many cases effective alternatives to using animals exist and that many laboratory procedures needlessly extend and prolong the pain suffered by animals.\r\nFarm, agriculture - While many outright oppose all killing of animals for food, the majority of animal protection in this regard is focused on the treatment and living conditions of animals prior to and during slaughter. Many factory farms are known to keep animals in confinement for the duration of their lives, subject them to overcrowding and force-feeding, and employ inhumane slaughtering methods.\r\nFur - This is perhaps one of the most visible issues in animal protection activism. Opposition to the practice of killing animals for fur clothing is not only in principle but also based on the treatment of animals on fur farms. Cramped and filthy living conditions, inhumane capture methods, and cruel slaughtering methods are among the many objections made by activists to the fur industry.    ﻿\r\n','<p>Each year, 25 million animals are used in the United States for experiments, 10 billion land animals are processed for food, 30 million are killed for fur, up to 75 million dogs and 85 million cats are kept as pets, and hundreds of thousands of wild and domestic animals are used for human entertainment.<br />In all, the commercial and domestic use of animals by humans presents a situation that is ripe for animal mistreatment and suffering.The primary settings and issues that animal welfare and protection efforts address include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Domestic neglect and abuse</strong> - While direct abuse of animals is certainly a problem in many households, neglect through inadequate feeding, shelter, and general care is a less noticeable but much more prevalent form of domestic animal cruelty.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Animal shelter euthanasia</strong> - Pet abandonment, as well as general overpopulation of pets that results from irresponsible breeding, low adoption rates, and lack of spaying and neutering, leads to overcrowding in shelters. Over half of all dogs and cats entering shelters are eventually euthanized.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Use in entertainment</strong> - Dogfights, cockfights and other cruel sports are the most visible forms of animal cruelty in entertainment. But settings such as circuses, zoos, races, transportation, and even TV and film are opportunities where animals may be mistreated and abused.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Experiments and testing</strong> - Animals are routinely used to conduct scientific research or to test the safety of cosmetics, chemicals and other products. Critics claim that in many cases effective alternatives to using animals exist and that many laboratory procedures needlessly extend and prolong the pain suffered by animals.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Farm, agriculture</strong> - While many outright oppose all killing of animals for food, the majority of animal protection in this regard is focused on the treatment and living conditions of animals prior to and during slaughter. Many factory farms are known to keep animals in confinement for the duration of their lives, subject them to overcrowding and force-feeding, and employ inhumane slaughtering methods.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Fur</strong> - This is perhaps one of the most visible issues in animal protection activism. Opposition to the practice of killing animals for fur clothing is not only in principle but also based on the treatment of animals on fur farms. Cramped and filthy living conditions, inhumane capture methods, and cruel slaughtering methods are among the many objections made by activists to the fur industry.    ﻿</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28659,219,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','While animal protection and welfare is an issue that garners broad public and national attention, the majority of actual animal protection activities take place on the local level.Local non-profit humane societies throughout the country perform various protection functions in their communities. Activities include feeding and shelter for stray animals, pet adoption, veterinary services, spaying and neutering, community education, and local watchdogging.On a national level, organizations such as The Humane Society, The American Humane Association, People for the Ethical Treatment of animals (PETA), and The American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (ASPCA) pursue animal protection and welfare goals on a broader scale. Largely operating as member-supported organizations, their activities primarily include:\r\n\r\nPublic education and awareness&nbsp;\r\nPolicy advocacy and lobbying\r\nAnimal cruelty documentation and research&nbsp;\r\nGrassroots mobilization directed toward businesses and government﻿\r\n\r\nCertification and auditing of products are also common activities among national organizations that fight against animal abuse and cruelty. These programs offer third-party independent verification programs to companies and products, including food and cosmetics, to ensure that products have been produced without cruelty or abuse to animals. The American Humane Certified program by the American Humane Association was the first such program in the United States.    ﻿','<p>While animal protection and welfare is an issue that garners broad public and national attention, the majority of actual animal protection activities take place on the local level.<br /><br />Local non-profit humane societies throughout the country perform various protection functions in their communities. Activities include feeding and shelter for stray animals, pet adoption, veterinary services, spaying and neutering, community education, and local watchdogging.On a national level, organizations such as The Humane Society, The American Humane Association, People for the Ethical Treatment of animals (PETA), and The American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (ASPCA) pursue animal protection and welfare goals on a broader scale. Largely operating as member-supported organizations, their activities primarily include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Public education and awareness&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Policy advocacy and lobbying</li>\r\n<li>Animal cruelty documentation and research&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Grassroots mobilization directed toward businesses and government﻿</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Certification and auditing of products are also common activities among national organizations that fight against animal abuse and cruelty. These programs offer third-party independent verification programs to companies and products, including food and cosmetics, to ensure that products have been produced without cruelty or abuse to animals. The American Humane Certified program by the American Humane Association was the first such program in the United States.    ﻿</p>'),(28660,219,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nPeople for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA): The Issues\r\nThe Humane Society: Issues\r\nAmerican Humane Association: Animal Abuse Factsheets\r\nUSDA: Animal Welfare Act Information\r\n\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source: Natural Resources Defense Council','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.peta.org/issues/default.aspx\">People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA): The Issues</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.humanesociety.org/issues/\">The Humane Society: Issues</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.americanhumane.org/animals/stop-animal-abuse/fact-sheets/\">American Humane Association: Animal Abuse Factsheets</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aphis.usda.gov/animal_welfare/awa_info.shtml\">USDA: Animal Welfare Act Information</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br />\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source: Natural Resources Defense Council</em></p>'),(28661,219,21,'left',1,'Organizations Working on this Issue','\r\nThe Humane Society of the United States\r\nNatural Resources Defense Council\r\nDefenders of Wildlife ﻿\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"/humanesociety\">The Humane Society of the United States</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/naturalresourcesdefensecouncil\">Natural Resources Defense Council</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/defendersofwildlife\">Defenders of Wildlife</a> ﻿</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28664,193,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','Malaria is caused by a parasite spread to humans through the bite of infected mosquitoes. If let untreated, it can cause severe complications and death. Malaria is prevalent in tropical and subtropical regions that receive significant amounts of rainfall and maintain warm temperatures year-round. Worldwide, malaria kills between 700,000 and 1,000,000 people every year.  In the 1640s, Europeans used bark from the cinchona tree containing quinine to treat malaria, and in 1820 quinine was first extracted and isolated as an antimalarial drug. In the 20th century, cloroquine&nbsp;and artemisinins were also discovered to be effective at combatting malaria. However despite almost 400 years of innovation and scientific discovery in antimalarial medication, every 45 seconds a child in Africa will die from malaria. Who is affected by malaria? Malaria is a serious problem in parts of South America, Southeast Asia, and Africa. In Sub-Saharan Africa, the most common mosquito is an incredibly effective carrier of malaria. Pregnant women and children are the biggest groups targeted; 90 percent of annual deaths from malaria occur in Africa, and 70 percent of deaths occurring in children under 5. With 50 percent of the world\'s population at risk for infection, an estimate $12,000,000,000 is spent per year on costs related to malaria such as medicine, hospital visits, and funeral costs.  Why has malaria only been eradicated in parts of the world? In the United States, malaria has been eradicated since the 1950s. Barriers preventing eradication in areas with high infection, like Africa, include political instability, extreme poverty, and adoption of anti-malaria strategies.&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPoverty: Many citizens living in areas with high risk of infection are unable to afford medication. In countries where families may live on less than $2 a day, even the seemingly negligible cost of $5 for a mosquito net that will save lives is difficult to afford. Anti-malaria medication may cost even more than nets. While medication is often free of charge in public health clinics, estimates indicate that 60% of malaria patients in Sub-Saharan Africa buy their medication from the private sector. Patients may be unable to take the work off necessary to travel to a health clinic, especially if they live in isolated, rural areas. Even if patients are able to receive treatment, 65% of malaria cases are treated without a diagnostic test, paving way for drug resistance.\r\nAdoption and use of mosquito nets: &nbsp;Actual adoption and use of mosquito nets is a barrier often faced by aid organizations. Data shows that nearly half of Africans who have access to nets refuse to sleep under them. This may be partly due to the limits of the ventilation provided by the nets, which is a challenge in the hot and humid environments where malaria thrives. Aid groups debate the most effective ways to distribute nets and ensure their appropriate use.&nbsp;\r\nPolitical Instability: In countries plagued by war and political turmoil, ruling parties may be resistant to receiving foreign aid, even if that aid comes in the form of mosquito nets or antimalarial drugs.&nbsp; While key prevention techniques, such as sleeping under mosquito nets treated with pesticide, and treatment options are well known, areas with political instability are often unable to successfully implement strategies to curb malaria infection.\r\n\r\nWhile The World Health Organization estimates an increase from $1.5 billion to $1.8 billion in international funding for malaria control between 2009 and 2010, this number still falls short of the $6 billion needed for worldwide malaria control.','<p>Malaria is caused by a parasite spread to humans through the bite of infected mosquitoes. If let untreated, it can cause severe complications and death. Malaria is prevalent in tropical and subtropical regions that receive significant amounts of rainfall and maintain warm temperatures year-round. Worldwide, malaria kills between 700,000 and 1,000,000 people every year. <br /><br /> In the 1640s, Europeans used bark from the cinchona tree containing quinine to treat malaria, and in 1820 quinine was first extracted and isolated as an antimalarial drug. In the 20th century, cloroquine&nbsp;and artemisinins were also discovered to be effective at combatting malaria. However despite almost 400 years of innovation and scientific discovery in antimalarial medication, every 45 seconds a child in Africa will die from malaria.<br /><br /> <em>Who is affected by malaria?</em><br /><br /> Malaria is a serious problem in parts of South America, Southeast Asia, and Africa. In Sub-Saharan Africa, the most common mosquito is an incredibly effective carrier of malaria. Pregnant women and children are the biggest groups targeted; 90 percent of annual deaths from malaria occur in Africa, and 70 percent of deaths occurring in children under 5. With 50 percent of the world\'s population at risk for infection, an estimate $12,000,000,000 is spent per year on costs related to malaria such as medicine, hospital visits, and funeral costs. <br /><br /> <em>Why has malaria only been eradicated in parts of the world?</em><br /><br /> In the United States, malaria has been eradicated since the 1950s. Barriers preventing eradication in areas with high infection, like Africa, include political instability, extreme poverty, and adoption of anti-malaria strategies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Poverty:</strong> Many citizens living in areas with high risk of infection are unable to afford medication. In countries where families may live on less than $2 a day, even the seemingly negligible cost of $5 for a mosquito net that will save lives is difficult to afford. Anti-malaria medication may cost even more than nets. While medication is often free of charge in public health clinics, estimates indicate that 60% of malaria patients in Sub-Saharan Africa buy their medication from the private sector. Patients may be unable to take the work off necessary to travel to a health clinic, especially if they live in isolated, rural areas. Even if patients are able to receive treatment, 65% of malaria cases are treated without a diagnostic test, paving way for drug resistance.<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Adoption and use of mosquito nets: &nbsp;</strong>Actual adoption and use of mosquito nets is a barrier often faced by aid organizations. Data shows that nearly half of Africans who have access to nets refuse to sleep under them. This may be partly due to the limits of the ventilation provided by the nets, which is a challenge in the hot and humid environments where malaria thrives. Aid groups debate the most effective ways to distribute nets and ensure their appropriate use.&nbsp;<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Political Instability:</strong> In countries plagued by war and political turmoil, ruling parties may be resistant to receiving foreign aid, even if that aid comes in the form of mosquito nets or antimalarial drugs.&nbsp; While key prevention techniques, such as sleeping under mosquito nets treated with pesticide, and treatment options are well known, areas with political instability are often unable to successfully implement strategies to curb malaria infection.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>While The World Health Organization estimates an increase from $1.5 billion to $1.8 billion in international funding for malaria control between 2009 and 2010, this number still falls short of the $6 billion needed for worldwide malaria control.</p>'),(28665,193,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Three components are needed for successful malarial prevention and treatment: \r\n\r\nAffordable malaria medication: Many organizations are working with drug companies in the private sector to provide affordable malarial medication for developing countries. In countries where malaria can account for up to 40 percent of all public health expenditures, the need for a reliable and affordable source of medication is great.\r\nInsecticide-treated nets (ITNs): ITNs have proven to be the most cost effective method of malaria prevention. Nets that emit insecticide are placed around beds to protect sleeping families. New technologies are emerging to create long lasting insecticide-treated nets (LLINs) that will emit insecticide for up to five years. In mid-2010, the World Health Organization estimated 40 percent of families in Africa owned at least one ITN. \r\nAffordable diagnostic tests: Distribution of cheap and reliable diagnostic tests could increase scientists\' ability to track different strains of malaria. Diagnostic tests can help reduce drug-resistance by determining the best course of treatment for individual patients.\r\n','<p><strong></strong>Three components are needed for successful malarial prevention and treatment: <strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Affordable malaria medication: </strong>Many organizations are working with drug companies in the private sector to provide affordable malarial medication for developing countries. In countries where malaria can account for up to 40 percent of all public health expenditures, the need for a reliable and affordable source of medication is great.<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Insecticide-treated nets (ITNs): </strong>ITNs have proven to be the most cost effective method of malaria prevention. Nets that emit insecticide are placed around beds to protect sleeping families. New technologies are emerging to create long lasting insecticide-treated nets (LLINs) that will emit insecticide for up to five years. In mid-2010, the World Health Organization estimated 40 percent of families in Africa owned at least one ITN. </li>\r\n<li><strong>Affordable diagnostic tests: </strong>Distribution of cheap and reliable diagnostic tests could increase scientists\' ability to track different strains of malaria. Diagnostic tests can help reduce drug-resistance by determining the best course of treatment for individual patients.</li>\r\n</ol>'),(28666,193,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nWorld Health Organization: Malaria Page\r\nCenter for Disease Control: Malaria page \r\nThe Global Fund: Malaria page \r\nBill and Melinda Gates Foundation: Progress Against Malaria (PDF)\r\n\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source:&nbsp;Malaria No More﻿','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.who.int/topics/malaria/en/\">World Health Organization: Malaria Page</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/MALARIA/\">Center for Disease Control: Malaria page </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.theglobalfund.org/en/about/diseases/malaria/\">The Global Fund: Malaria page</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.gatesfoundation.org/livingproofproject/Documents/progress-against-malaria.pdf\">Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation: Progress Against Malaria </a>(PDF)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source:&nbsp;Malaria No More﻿</em></p>'),(28667,9,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','More than 190 million Americans-two-thirds of the U.S. population-are overweight or obese. In the past 30 years, obesity rates have more than doubled while childhood obesity rates have tripled, with over 17% of children now considered obese. Obesity is associated with an increased risk for cardiovascular diseases, hypertension, stroke, Type 2 diabetes, asthma, and coronary heart disease. 9.1 percent of America\'s annual health care spending, or $147,000,000,000, is spent on obesity-related treatment.  The root causes of obesity lie in interlocking systems of economic inequality, lack of access to healthcare, and lack of education. These inequalities support the two biggest contributors to obesity: lack of proper nutrition and lack of exercise. Lack of Proper Nutrition&nbsp;  Inadequate nutrition in the U.S. has two main components: lack of access to healthy food and lack of accountability on the part of the food industry. As more Americans move to urban environments, many live in areas without access to community gardens, farmer\'s markets, or other sources of fresh produce. Between traveling longer distances to procure fresh food or using convenience stores and fast-food chains with little fresh produce or locally-sourced whole foods, many are influenced by economic and time constraints to choose the latter. More than 55 million children are enrolled in public schools, where the advertising and sale of sugary soft drinks, candy, and other high caloric foods is rampant. In addition, more than 12 million children participate in some form of daycare outside the home, where licensing regulations around healthy food are often relaxed.  Food today is engineered to be grown quickly, shipped long distances, and stocked on shelves for extended periods of time; this mean less fresh produce and whole foods, and more processed foods packed with preservatives. In addition, many foods full of high-fructose corn syrup and other processed ingredients are able to apply \"healthy\" or \"organic\" labels, which may mislead consumers.  Government may recommend one set of eating habits, but government policies may promote another entirely. A 2010 article in The New York Times showed the misalignment between federal recommendations for the number of servings of protein per day including meat and dairy (6 servings, compared to 9 of fruits and vegetables and 11 of whole grains) and the percentage of federal subsidies for food production (73.8 percent for meat and dairy compared to 13.23 percent for grains). Lack of Exercise Many families live in neighborhoods where they are unable to walk to school, parks, community events, or grocery stores. This promotes a culture in which families increasingly rely on cars for transportation, forgoing a healthy walk for a 5-minute drive. Moreso than ever, the American working life involves sitting at a desk for up to 10 hours a day. A sedentary working life combined with a dependence on cars for transportation and the amount of time spent walking or engaging in exercise on a daily basis has quickly become negligible. On average, children spend 7.5 hours a day devoted to media, including computers and television. Many children also receive little to no physical exercise at school. While 60 minutes of aerobic exercise is recommended a day, in 2009 only 33 percent of students attended a daily physical education class.','<p>More than 190 million Americans-two-thirds of the U.S. population-are overweight or obese. In the past 30 years, obesity rates have more than doubled while childhood obesity rates have tripled, with over 17% of children now considered obese. Obesity is associated with an increased risk for cardiovascular diseases, hypertension, stroke, Type 2 diabetes, asthma, and coronary heart disease. 9.1 percent of America\'s annual health care spending, or $147,000,000,000, is spent on obesity-related treatment. <br /><br /> The root causes of obesity lie in interlocking systems of economic inequality, lack of access to healthcare, and lack of education. These inequalities support the two biggest contributors to obesity: lack of proper nutrition and lack of exercise.<br /><br /> <em>Lack of Proper Nutrition</em>&nbsp; <br /><br /> Inadequate nutrition in the U.S. has two main components: lack of access to healthy food and lack of accountability on the part of the food industry. As more Americans move to urban environments, many live in areas without access to community gardens, farmer\'s markets, or other sources of fresh produce. Between traveling longer distances to procure fresh food or using convenience stores and fast-food chains with little fresh produce or locally-sourced whole foods, many are influenced by economic and time constraints to choose the latter.<br /><br /> More than 55 million children are enrolled in public schools, where the advertising and sale of sugary soft drinks, candy, and other high caloric foods is rampant. In addition, more than 12 million children participate in some form of daycare outside the home, where licensing regulations around healthy food are often relaxed. <br /><br /> Food today is engineered to be grown quickly, shipped long distances, and stocked on shelves for extended periods of time; this mean less fresh produce and whole foods, and more processed foods packed with preservatives. In addition, many foods full of high-fructose corn syrup and other processed ingredients are able to apply \"healthy\" or \"organic\" labels, which may mislead consumers. <br /><br /> Government may recommend one set of eating habits, but government policies may promote another entirely. A 2010 article in <em>The New York Times </em>showed the misalignment between federal recommendations for the number of servings of protein per day including meat and dairy (6 servings, compared to 9 of fruits and vegetables and 11 of whole grains) and the percentage of federal subsidies for food production (73.8 percent for meat and dairy compared to 13.23 percent for grains).<br /><br /> <em>Lack of Exercise</em><br /><br /> Many families live in neighborhoods where they are unable to walk to school, parks, community events, or grocery stores. This promotes a culture in which families increasingly rely on cars for transportation, forgoing a healthy walk for a 5-minute drive. Moreso than ever, the American working life involves sitting at a desk for up to 10 hours a day. A sedentary working life combined with a dependence on cars for transportation and the amount of time spent walking or engaging in exercise on a daily basis has quickly become negligible.<br /><br /> On average, children spend 7.5 hours a day devoted to media, including computers and television. Many children also receive little to no physical exercise at school. While 60 minutes of aerobic exercise is recommended a day, in 2009 only 33 percent of students attended a daily physical education class.</p>'),(28668,9,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','The Center for Disease Control and First Lady Michelle Obama\'s Let\'s Move initiatives are two current resources for individuals trying to develop healthy eating and exercise practices. However, truly solving the obesity epidemic will require long-term lifestyle changes for Americans as well as systemic changes to America\'s food system. These changes necessitate an increase in healthy food and exercise education and significant changes to the food industry:\r\n\r\nEducation: While information surrounding healthy eating and exercise habits is available, it can be hard to discern what advice to follow.&nbsp; Conflicting sources promote calorie counting vs. portion control and cardio vs. strength training.&nbsp; Americans spend $40 million a year on weight-loss programs; however, according to a study in The New England Journal of Medicine, within a year most individuals will gain back one-third of the weight they lose. Under the Obama administration, the USDA has released a new set of basic dietary guidelines and replaced the food pyramid with Choose My Plate, an way for Americans to understand what they should be eating. Educating youth about good eating and exercise habits is also an important step to creating lifelong practices that promote a healthy lifestyle.\r\nRewarding Production of Healthy Food: Fresh fruits and vegetables make minimal profits for food companies. However cash crops like corn, soybeans, and wheat used to make sweeteners and preservatives are highly profitable due to government subsidies. In order to promote eating healthy, government subsidies need to reward produce growers and farmers using sustainable, eco-friendly practices.&nbsp; And communities must invest in supporting locally sourced organic food.&nbsp;\r\nRegulations on Food: The interests of the food industry can often affect government regulations. An article published in the Public Library of Science\'s medical journal found that no industry-funded reports addressing the biomedical effects of milk, juice, and soft drinks reported unfavorable conclusions, compared to 37 percent of reports with no industry funding. Stricter regulations on how foods are labeled can help to empower consumers to make healthy decisions. The FDA is currently working to redesign nutritional information on food products, increasing consumer awareness of what they\'re really buying. \r\n\r\nMany communities creating environments and life-style practices that promote healthy decisions. For example, urban planners, real-estate developers, and homeowners and renters are increasingly advocating for walkable neighborhoods that seek to create communities where children are able to walk to school, families can walk to stores, and housing is diverse enough to accommodate people with different socio-economic, age, and family planning realities.﻿','<p>The <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/healthyweight/\">Center for Disease Control</a> and First Lady Michelle Obama\'s <a href=\"http://www.letsmove.gov/\">Let\'s Move</a> initiatives are two current resources for individuals trying to develop healthy eating and exercise practices. However, truly solving the obesity epidemic will require long-term lifestyle changes for Americans as well as systemic changes to America\'s food system. These changes necessitate an increase in healthy food and exercise education and significant changes to the food industry:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Education: </strong>While information surrounding healthy eating and exercise habits is available, it can be hard to discern what advice to follow.&nbsp; Conflicting sources promote calorie counting vs. portion control and cardio vs. strength training.&nbsp; Americans spend $40 million a year on weight-loss programs; however, according to a study in <em>The New England Journal of Medicine, </em>within a year most individuals will gain back one-third of the weight they lose. Under the Obama administration, the USDA has released a new set of basic dietary guidelines and replaced the food pyramid with <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/\">Choose My Plate</a>, an way for Americans to understand what they should be eating. Educating youth about good eating and exercise habits is also an important step to creating lifelong practices that promote a healthy lifestyle.<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Rewarding Production of Healthy Food: </strong>Fresh fruits and vegetables make minimal profits for food companies. However cash crops like corn, soybeans, and wheat used to make sweeteners and preservatives are highly profitable due to government subsidies. In order to promote eating healthy, government subsidies need to reward produce growers and farmers using sustainable, eco-friendly practices.&nbsp; And communities must invest in supporting locally sourced organic food.&nbsp;<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Regulations on Food: </strong>The interests of the food industry can often affect government regulations. An article published in the Public Library of Science\'s medical journal found that no industry-funded reports addressing the biomedical effects of milk, juice, and soft drinks reported unfavorable conclusions, compared to 37 percent of reports with no industry funding. Stricter regulations on how foods are labeled can help to empower consumers to make healthy decisions. The FDA is currently working to redesign nutritional information on food products, increasing consumer awareness of what they\'re really buying. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Many communities creating environments and life-style practices that promote healthy decisions. For example, urban planners, real-estate developers, and homeowners and renters are increasingly advocating for walkable neighborhoods that seek to create communities where children are able to walk to school, families can walk to stores, and housing is diverse enough to accommodate people with different socio-economic, age, and family planning realities.﻿</p>'),(28669,193,21,'left',1,'Organizations Working on this Issue','\r\nAgainst Malaria Foundation\r\nThe Global Fund\r\nBill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation\r\nTAMTAM\r\nMalaria No More\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"/againstmalariafoundation\">Against Malaria Foundation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/theglobalfund\">The Global Fund</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/billmelindagatesfoundation\">Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/tamtamafrica\">TAMTAM</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/malarianomore\">Malaria No More</a></li>\r\n</ul>'),(28670,9,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nObesity.org Statistics\r\nCDC Obesity Page \r\nUSDA Food and Nutrition Information Center\r\n\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source: USDA','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.obesity.org/resources-for/obesity-statistics.htm\">Obesity.org Statistics</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/\">CDC Obesity Page </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://fnic.nal.usda.gov/nal_display/index.php?info_center=4&amp;tax_level=1\">USDA Food and Nutrition Information Center</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br />\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source: USDA</em></p>'),(28673,9,21,'left',1,'Organizations working on this issue','\r\nLet\'s Move \r\nThe Obesity Society \r\nThe American Obesity Association \r\nShape Up America!\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.letsmove.gov/\">Let\'s Move</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.obesity.org/\">The Obesity Society </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.healthfinder.gov/orgs/hr3020.htm\">The American Obesity Association </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.shapeup.org/\">Shape Up America!</a></li>\r\n</ul>'),(28675,176,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','Movements for women\'s rights seek to address the unique challenges women face gaining access to healthcare, education, economic and political participation, and fundamental human and civil rights. Women&nbsp;perform 66 percent of the world\'s work, produce 50 percent of the&nbsp;food, yet earn 10 percent of the income and&nbsp;own&nbsp;just 1 percent of the&nbsp;property. Today, numerous governmental and NGO forces are working across the globe to ensure equality for women. Here are a few of the sectors they\'re working in:  Access to Education 130 million global youth are currently without education. Of these, 70 percent are girls. Girls may be excluded from primary, secondary, and higher education for various reasons including cultural or religious attitudes towards women and extreme poverty. Expending resources on educating girls is also often seen as a wasteful investment since girls may be married as young as 15 in many developing regions.  However studies show that women with an extra year of primary school will make 10-20 percent higher wages, and an extra year of secondary school correlates to a wage increase of 15-25 percent. Studies also show that women tend to invest 90 percent of their income back into their families and communities, meaning that the benefits of continued enrollment for girls are lasting and community-wide.  Health and Reproductive Rights Lack of affordable, accessible healthcare is one of the most pervasive problems facing women around the globe. Especially in rural, isolated areas, many women are forced to go without adequate medical assistance. When it comes to reproductive care, this can be deadly.  More than 600,000 women die annually during pregnancy and childbirth. Of the 15 million adolescents age 15 - 19 who give birth every year, 60,000 will die in the course of their pregnancy or childbirth, making pregnancy the leading cause of death for adolescent females. An additional 4.4 million girls age 15 - 19 will receive unsafe abortions annually. In Western Europe the chances of dying from in childbirth are 1 in 3,200, in sub-Saharan Africa, they\'re 1 in 13.  Violence Against Women and Girls In many developed and developing areas of the world women\'s safety is continually threatened by domestic violence, sexual assault, and other forms of violence. In developing countries the risk can be especially high due to a lack of legal enforcement or cultural strictures prohibiting violence against women. One third of countries have no official laws against domestic violence. In 17 of 41 countries interviewed by the UN, a quarter or more of men believe it is acceptable for a man to beat his wife. Areas with tolerant attitudes towards violence against women may also be less likely to enact legislation against practices like marital rape or female genital mutilation/cutting.  Attitudes against women often intersect with other forms of cultural, social, economic, and racial oppression to further legitimize violence. Women working as domestic workers, for instance, face disproportionately high instances of violence and sexual harassment. While rape and sexual violence have historically been used as weapons in warfare, it wasn\'t until 1998 that the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda dictated that rape could constitute genocide under international law. Until the 2001 International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia, rape was not included in the definition of crimes against humanity. &nbsp;\r\nPolitical and Economic Access Women without opportunities for income generation are unable to participate fully in their communities, leaving them vulnerable to further social exclusion and marginalization. On average, women perform 66% of the world\'s work and produce 50% of the world\'s food, yet they earn only 10% of the world\'s income and own 1% of the world\'s land. Inheritance and land rights remain obscure for many women in the developing world. Without the economic and social resources to run and work in sustainable business environments, the number of women living in poverty will continue to rise.&nbsp;\r\nA lack of political access still plagues many women in the developing world as well, further contributing to their marginalization. Even in developed regions, women have achieved only as high as 30 percent of all ministerial positions in a country, and nowhere in the world have women achieved that percentage of representation in a parliament. Lack of adequate political access, whether it\'s representation in government or the ability to vote, undermines political and social movements towards equality for women.','<p>Movements for women\'s rights seek to address the unique challenges women face gaining access to healthcare, education, economic and political participation, and fundamental human and civil rights. Women&nbsp;perform 66 percent of the world\'s work, produce 50 percent of the&nbsp;food, yet earn 10 percent of the income and&nbsp;own&nbsp;just 1 percent of the&nbsp;property. Today, numerous governmental and NGO forces are working across the globe to ensure equality for women. Here are a few of the sectors they\'re working in: <br /><br /> <em>Access to Education</em><br /><br /> 130 million global youth are currently without education. Of these, 70 percent are girls. Girls may be excluded from primary, secondary, and higher education for various reasons including cultural or religious attitudes towards women and extreme poverty. Expending resources on educating girls is also often seen as a wasteful investment since girls may be married as young as 15 in many developing regions. <br /><br /> However studies show that women with an extra year of primary school will make 10-20 percent higher wages, and an extra year of secondary school correlates to a wage increase of 15-25 percent. Studies also show that women tend to invest 90 percent of their income back into their families and communities, meaning that the benefits of continued enrollment for girls are lasting and community-wide. <br /><br /> <em>Health and Reproductive Rights</em><br /><br /> Lack of affordable, accessible healthcare is one of the most pervasive problems facing women around the globe. Especially in rural, isolated areas, many women are forced to go without adequate medical assistance. When it comes to reproductive care, this can be deadly. <br /><br /> More than 600,000 women die annually during pregnancy and childbirth. Of the 15 million adolescents age 15 - 19 who give birth every year, 60,000 will die in the course of their pregnancy or childbirth, making pregnancy the leading cause of death for adolescent females. An additional 4.4 million girls age 15 - 19 will receive unsafe abortions annually. In Western Europe the chances of dying from in childbirth are 1 in 3,200, in sub-Saharan Africa, they\'re 1 in 13. <br /><br /> <em>Violence Against Women and Girls</em><br /><br /> In many developed and developing areas of the world women\'s safety is continually threatened by domestic violence, sexual assault, and other forms of violence. In developing countries the risk can be especially high due to a lack of legal enforcement or cultural strictures prohibiting violence against women. One third of countries have no official laws against domestic violence. In 17 of 41 countries interviewed by the UN, a quarter or more of men believe it is acceptable for a man to beat his wife. Areas with tolerant attitudes towards violence against women may also be less likely to enact legislation against practices like marital rape or female genital mutilation/cutting. <br /><br /> Attitudes against women often intersect with other forms of cultural, social, economic, and racial oppression to further legitimize violence. Women working as domestic workers, for instance, face disproportionately high instances of violence and sexual harassment. While rape and sexual violence have historically been used as weapons in warfare, it wasn\'t until 1998 that the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda dictated that rape could constitute genocide under international law. Until the 2001 International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia, rape was not included in the definition of crimes against humanity. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Political and Economic Access</em><br /><br /> Women without opportunities for income generation are unable to participate fully in their communities, leaving them vulnerable to further social exclusion and marginalization. On average, women perform 66% of the world\'s work and produce 50% of the world\'s food, yet they earn only 10% of the world\'s income and own 1% of the world\'s land. Inheritance and land rights remain obscure for many women in the developing world. Without the economic and social resources to run and work in sustainable business environments, the number of women living in poverty will continue to rise.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A lack of political access still plagues many women in the developing world as well, further contributing to their marginalization. Even in developed regions, women have achieved only as high as 30 percent of all ministerial positions in a country, and nowhere in the world have women achieved that percentage of representation in a parliament. Lack of adequate political access, whether it\'s representation in government or the ability to vote, undermines political and social movements towards equality for women.</p>'),(28676,176,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','\r\n Microenterprise: Recently, social sector solutions for women in developing countries have focused on creating equal economic access through job training, microfinance, and microenterprises. These strategies work to correct poverty imbalances and empower women working to change their lives. By providing women with the ability to build sustainable business practices, microenterprise can lift women out of poverty and revitalize an entire community.&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\nIncreased Education Opportunities: Making it possible for young girls to stay in school decreases the likelihood of child marriage, unwanted pregnancies, and lifelong poverty. Girls who receive seven or more years of education marry an average of four years later and have 2.2 fewer children.&nbsp;\r\nComprehensive Healthcare for Women: Without access to reproductive options and care, there is little hope women will be able to significantly improve their lives. Comprehensive healthcare includes access (more clinics) and affordable care (governmental programs to help pay for medication and birth control) as well as awareness and advocacy. 75 percent of people age 15 - 24 living with HIV in Africa are women, however in a recent UN survey, interviewers found that in Nigeria, Sierra Leone, and Mali, over 50 percent of women reported not being able to ask their partners to use condoms. Advocacy and awareness campaigns can help reduce practices that put women at risk. \r\n','<ul>\r\n<li> <strong>Microenterprise:</strong> Recently, social sector solutions for women in developing countries have focused on creating equal economic access through job training, microfinance, and microenterprises. These strategies work to correct poverty imbalances and empower women working to change their lives. By providing women with the ability to build sustainable business practices, microenterprise can lift women out of poverty and revitalize an entire community.&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Increased Education Opportunities: </strong>Making it possible for young girls to stay in school decreases the likelihood of child marriage, unwanted pregnancies, and lifelong poverty. Girls who receive seven or more years of education marry an average of four years later and have 2.2 fewer children.&nbsp;<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Comprehensive Healthcare for Women:<em> </em></strong>Without access to reproductive options and care, there is little hope women will be able to significantly improve their lives. Comprehensive healthcare includes access (more clinics) and affordable care (governmental programs to help pay for medication and birth control) as well as awareness and advocacy. 75 percent of people age 15 - 24 living with HIV in Africa are women, however in a recent UN survey, interviewers found that in Nigeria, Sierra Leone, and Mali, over 50 percent of women reported not being able to ask their partners to use condoms. Advocacy and awareness campaigns can help reduce practices that put women at risk. </li>\r\n</ul>'),(28677,176,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nUN: Progress of the World\'s Women&nbsp; \r\nUN Women&nbsp; \r\nHuman Rights Watch: Women\'s Rights page       ﻿\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source: Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://progress.unwomen.org/\">UN: Progress of the World\'s Women</a>&nbsp; </li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.unwomen.org/\">UN Women</a>&nbsp; </li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.hrw.org/category/topic/women\">Human Rights Watch: Women\'s Rights page       ﻿</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>\r\n<p>Profile Photo Source: Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation</p>\r\n</em></p>'),(28679,176,21,'left',1,'Organizations Working on this Issue','\r\nLandesa\r\nPanzi Hospital of Bukavu \r\nGirl Effect\r\nWomen for Women International \r\nGlobal Fund for Women\r\n','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"/landesa\">Landesa</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/panzihospitalofbukavu\">Panzi Hospital of Bukavu </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/girleffect\">Girl Effect</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/womenforwomeninternational\">Women for Women International </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"/globalfundforwomen\">Global Fund for Women</a></li>\r\n</ul>'),(28681,157,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','According to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development-considered to be the most reliable source of statistical information on America\'s homeless population-the number of Americans experiencing homelessness on any given night in 2010 was almost 650,000. In all, 1.6 million people in the U.S. experienced homelessness at some point in the year. 60 percent of those were sheltered during their homelessness, with the rest living outdoors and in abandoned buildings, makeshift structures, or cars.\r\nFor most, homelessness is a transitory state. The majority of people who experience homelessness do so for a temporary period, from a few days up to several months. It is estimated that those who can be classified as \"chronically homeless\" -people with long histories of being homeless-currently number around 110,000. Those who are chronically homeless are often people with severe disabilities and people with mental illnesses. While shelters traditionally serve as the first line of aid for the homeless, they are anything but a perfect solution. Shelters are often overcrowded and chaotic environments. Inhabitants are forced to fight over limited resources and deal with the constant fear of theft and violence. Such conditions often force the homeless to prefer living on the street. Who are the homeless?\r\n\r\nThe U.S. sheltered homeless population is estimated to be 42 percent African-American, 38 percent white, 20 percent Hispanic, 4 percent Native American and 2 percent Asian.\r\nChildren under the age of 18 comprise almost 40 percent of the homeless population; 25 percent of the homeless are between the ages of 25 and 34.\r\n&nbsp;Two thirds of the homeless are individuals not considered to be a part of a family household.\r\nAfrican-Americans, men between the ages of 31 and 50, and people with disabilities are at the highest risk of becoming homeless.\r\nThose sheltered as individuals tend to be white men over the age of 30 with a reported disability\r\nAdults sheltered in families tend to be African-American women.\r\n&nbsp;The Veterans Affairs Department estimates that there are 107,000 homeless veterans on any given night.\r\nOver 70 percent of the homeless reside in cities.\r\nCalifornia, New York, Florida account for 40 percent of the nation\'s homeless.\r\n\r\nWhat are the causes?\r\nHomelessness in the United States is generally attributed to two primary causes:\r\n\r\nAn affordable housing shortage crisis throughout America\'s rental market has made it extremely difficult for low-income individuals and families to find housing they can afford. Affordability is generally defined as a home for which a renter pays no more than 30 percent of his/her income. Beyond that threshold, sacrifices must be made in basic human necessities like food, clothing, and health care. It is estimated that one in four households spend more than half of their income on housing. According to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, in no part of the United States can a minimum wage job currently provide enough income for a household to afford a two-bedroom apartment.\r\nPoverty as a result of unemployment, low wages, and cuts to basic public services provides the other side of the homelessness equation. A survey of cities by the US Conference of Mayors found unemployment to be the leading cause of homelessness for families. Coupled with a stagnant minimum wage since the 1970s and repeated cuts to public assistance since the 1980s, low-income individuals and families do not earn enough to afford basic housing throughout the country.\r\n\r\nOn an individual level, certain lifestyle and health and factors predispose individuals to homelessness. These include drug and alcohol abuse, severe physical disability, and mental illness. Domestic violence is a leading cause of homelessness among women, who must leave their homes and seek shelter elsewhere in order to avoid spousal abuse.','<p>According to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development-considered to be the most reliable source of statistical information on America\'s homeless population-the number of Americans experiencing homelessness on any given night in 2010 was almost 650,000. In all, 1.6 million people in the U.S. experienced homelessness at some point in the year. 60 percent of those were sheltered during their homelessness, with the rest living outdoors and in abandoned buildings, makeshift structures, or cars.</p>\r\n<p>For most, homelessness is a transitory state. The majority of people who experience homelessness do so for a temporary period, from a few days up to several months. It is estimated that those who can be classified as \"chronically homeless\" -people with long histories of being homeless-currently number around 110,000. Those who are chronically homeless are often people with severe disabilities and people with mental illnesses.<br /><br /> While shelters traditionally serve as the first line of aid for the homeless, they are anything but a perfect solution. Shelters are often overcrowded and chaotic environments. Inhabitants are forced to fight over limited resources and deal with the constant fear of theft and violence. Such conditions often force the homeless to prefer living on the street.<br /><br /> <em>Who are the homeless?</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The U.S. sheltered homeless population is estimated to be 42 percent African-American, 38 percent white, 20 percent Hispanic, 4 percent Native American and 2 percent Asian.</li>\r\n<li>Children under the age of 18 comprise almost 40 percent of the homeless population; 25 percent of the homeless are between the ages of 25 and 34.</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;Two thirds of the homeless are individuals not considered to be a part of a family household.</li>\r\n<li>African-Americans, men between the ages of 31 and 50, and people with disabilities are at the highest risk of becoming homeless.</li>\r\n<li>Those sheltered as individuals tend to be white men over the age of 30 with a reported disability</li>\r\n<li>Adults sheltered in families tend to be African-American women.</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;The Veterans Affairs Department estimates that there are 107,000 homeless veterans on any given night.</li>\r\n<li>Over 70 percent of the homeless reside in cities.</li>\r\n<li>California, New York, Florida account for 40 percent of the nation\'s homeless.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>What are the causes?</em></p>\r\n<p>Homelessness in the United States is generally attributed to two primary causes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>An affordable housing shortage crisis </strong>throughout America\'s rental market has made it extremely difficult for low-income individuals and families to find housing they can afford. Affordability is generally defined as a home for which a renter pays no more than 30 percent of his/her income. Beyond that threshold, sacrifices must be made in basic human necessities like food, clothing, and health care. It is estimated that one in four households spend more than half of their income on housing. According to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development,<strong> in no part of the United States can a minimum wage job currently provide enough income for a household to afford a two-bedroom apartment.</strong><strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Poverty</strong> as a result of unemployment, low wages, and cuts to basic public services provides the other side of the homelessness equation. A survey of cities by the US Conference of Mayors found <strong>unemployment to be the leading cause of homelessness for families</strong>. Coupled with a stagnant minimum wage since the 1970s and repeated cuts to public assistance since the 1980s, low-income individuals and families do not earn enough to afford basic housing throughout the country.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>On an individual level, certain lifestyle and health and factors predispose individuals to homelessness. These include drug and alcohol abuse, severe physical disability, and mental illness. Domestic violence is a leading cause of homelessness among women, who must leave their homes and seek shelter elsewhere in order to avoid spousal abuse.</p>'),(28682,157,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Solutions to homelessness fall into two basic categories:\r\n\r\nSolutions designed to relieve and rehabilitate those who have already fallen victim to homelessness\r\nSolutions to stem the tide of homelessness and prevent more people from becoming homeless.\r\n\r\nTreating homelessness For the former, shelters are not considered to be a solution but rather a form of humanitarian relief designed to shield people from the acute effects of homelessness. As stated before, shelters themselves can lead to further hardship and trauma, and some consider investments in shelters to be a diversion from long-term solutions. Non-profit organizations and government programs tasked with bringing people out of homelessness do so through a mix of addressing individual causes such as substance abuse, illness, and domestic violence, and directly providing short- and long-term housing. A recent trend in addressing homelessness favors the latter-a \"Housing First\" approach. Those who favor this approach maintain that addressing individual causes of homelessness becomes much more feasible once the individual returns to the stability of a permanent home. Rather than treating specific causes, this approach first places homeless people into housing as quickly as possible and then addresses individual conditions and circumstances. The U.S. Interagency Council on Homelessness, the agency that is tasked with coordinating the federal response to homelessness across all federal agencies, has endorsed Housing First as a best practice and top level policy recommendation. The U.S. government has to date funded more than 70,000 Housing First units since 2001. Organizations that address homelessness do so through material assistance and through policy advocacy that calls on the U.S. government to provide increased funding and attention to the plight of the homeless. Examples are National Coalition for the Homeless, National Alliance to End Homelessness, and National Coalition for Homeless Veterans. Solving homelessness Solutions to preventing homelessness and stemming its tide rest squarely on addressing the shortage of affordable housing in the United States. Addressing this problem largely rests on government policy and funding, channeled primarily through the U.S. Department on Housing and Urban Development (HUD). HUD considers the expansion of affordable housing to be at the core of its mission, and attempts to do so through a number of programs.\r\n\r\nGrants to state and local governments to build low-income housing\r\nGrants to non-profits to purchase home sites and establish sweat equity-based homeownership programs\r\nFunding for communities to reclaim and revitalize vacant properties and blighted neighborhoods\r\n\r\nIn addition to these programs, public housing-government-owned, subsidized housing offered to eligible low-income families, the elderly, and people with disabilities at affordable rent prices-is administered by HUD and also plays a major role in preventing homelessness. HUD estimates that 1.2 million households currently live in public rental housing. Maintaining and increasing funding for public housing is a major point of advocacy for organizations devoted to low income housing, like the National Low Income Housing Coalition. While many organizations work to advocate increased funding and programs, some organizations work directly to provide affordable housing to poor and low-income people. One example is Habitat for Humanity, an organization that directly builds affordable housing for those in need. Recent Developments:\r\n\r\nOne June 22, 2010, President Obama unveiled his administration\'s plan to end child and family homelessness in 10 years, and chronic and veteran homelessness in five. The \"Opening Doors\" plan is the first comprehensive federal effort to end homelessness.\r\n','<p>Solutions to homelessness fall into two basic categories:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Solutions designed to relieve and rehabilitate those who have already fallen victim to homelessness</li>\r\n<li>Solutions to stem the tide of homelessness and prevent more people from becoming homeless.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>Treating homelessness</em><br /><br /> For the former, shelters are not considered to be a solution but rather a form of humanitarian relief designed to shield people from the acute effects of homelessness. As stated before, shelters themselves can lead to further hardship and trauma, and some consider investments in shelters to be a diversion from long-term solutions.<br /><br /> Non-profit organizations and government programs tasked with bringing people out of homelessness do so through a mix of addressing individual causes such as substance abuse, illness, and domestic violence, and directly providing short- and long-term housing.<br /><br /> A recent trend in addressing homelessness favors the latter-a \"Housing First\" approach. Those who favor this approach maintain that addressing individual causes of homelessness becomes much more feasible once the individual returns to the stability of a permanent home. Rather than treating specific causes, this approach first places homeless people into housing as quickly as possible and then addresses individual conditions and circumstances. The U.S. Interagency Council on Homelessness, the agency that is tasked with coordinating the federal response to homelessness across all federal agencies, has endorsed Housing First as a best practice and top level policy recommendation. The U.S. government has to date funded more than 70,000 Housing First units since 2001.<br /><br /> Organizations that address homelessness do so through material assistance and through policy advocacy that calls on the U.S. government to provide increased funding and attention to the plight of the homeless. Examples are National Coalition for the Homeless, National Alliance to End Homelessness, and National Coalition for Homeless Veterans.<br /><br /> <em>Solving homelessness</em><br /><br /> Solutions to preventing homelessness and stemming its tide rest squarely on addressing the shortage of affordable housing in the United States.<br /><br /> Addressing this problem largely rests on government policy and funding, channeled primarily through the U.S. Department on Housing and Urban Development (HUD). HUD considers the expansion of affordable housing to be at the core of its mission, and attempts to do so through a number of programs.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Grants to state and local governments to build low-income housing</li>\r\n<li>Grants to non-profits to purchase home sites and establish sweat equity-based homeownership programs</li>\r\n<li>Funding for communities to reclaim and revitalize vacant properties and blighted neighborhoods</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In addition to these programs, public housing-government-owned, subsidized housing offered to eligible low-income families, the elderly, and people with disabilities at affordable rent prices-is administered by HUD and also plays a major role in preventing homelessness. HUD estimates that 1.2 million households currently live in public rental housing. Maintaining and increasing funding for public housing is a major point of advocacy for organizations devoted to low income housing, like the National Low Income Housing Coalition.<br /><br /> While many organizations work to advocate increased funding and programs, some organizations work directly to provide affordable housing to poor and low-income people. One example is Habitat for Humanity, an organization that directly builds affordable housing for those in need.<br /><br /> <em>Recent Developments:</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>One June 22, 2010, President Obama unveiled his administration\'s plan to end child and family homelessness in 10 years, and chronic and veteran homelessness in five. The \"Opening Doors\" plan is the first comprehensive federal effort to end homelessness.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28686,178,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','Developing countries represent only 11 percent of the global population exposed to natural disasters and emergencies, but account for 53 percent of all casualties. The increased vulnerability of developing countries to catastrophic effects from natural disasters like earthquakes, hurricanes, droughts, and floods can be attributed to multiple factors:\r\n\r\nLack of economic resources for an effective response\r\nHigh number of people residing on vulnerable terrain like flood plains and hillsides\r\nLack of in-country disaster planning and expertise\r\nWeaker physical infrastructure and lack of proper building codes and standards\r\nPoor domestic health systems\r\nPre-existing poverty, famines, epidemics, conflict\r\n\r\nOther factors such as political, geographical, and cultural isolation can compound these challenges by complicating emergency responses from international agencies and organizations. Rising frequency exposure Various global trends are resulting in increased exposure to and frequency of natural hazards:\r\n\r\nClimate change is increasing the frequency of disasters, particularly ones related to sea-level rise, according to international and scientific agencies.\r\nExploding coastal population growth is exposing more people to natural hazards like tsunamis and floods.\r\nRising urbanization is making more of the world\'s population vulnerable to earthquakes.\r\nEnvironmental degradation as a result of logging and destruction of wetlands make flooding more likely.\r\n','<p>Developing countries represent only 11 percent of the global population exposed to natural disasters and emergencies, but account for 53 percent of all casualties.<br /><br /> The increased vulnerability of developing countries to catastrophic effects from natural disasters like earthquakes, hurricanes, droughts, and floods can be attributed to multiple factors:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lack of economic resources for an effective response</li>\r\n<li>High number of people residing on vulnerable terrain like flood plains and hillsides</li>\r\n<li>Lack of in-country disaster planning and expertise</li>\r\n<li>Weaker physical infrastructure and lack of proper building codes and standards</li>\r\n<li>Poor domestic health systems</li>\r\n<li>Pre-existing poverty, famines, epidemics, conflict</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Other factors such as political, geographical, and cultural isolation can compound these challenges by complicating emergency responses from international agencies and organizations.<br /><br /> <em>Rising frequency exposure</em><br /><br /> Various global trends are resulting in increased exposure to and frequency of natural hazards:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Climate change</strong> is increasing the frequency of disasters, particularly ones related to sea-level rise, according to international and scientific agencies.<strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Exploding coastal population growth</strong> is exposing more people to natural hazards like tsunamis and floods.<strong></strong><strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Rising urbanization</strong> is making more of the world\'s population vulnerable to earthquakes.<strong></strong><strong></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Environmental degradation</strong> as a result of logging and destruction of wetlands make flooding more likely.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28687,178,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Improving disaster response in developing countries relies on a combination of deploying effective international aid while also helping countries themselves become more resilient and less vulnerable to disaster. Disaster reduction In most disasters, the majority of lives are lost within the first few hours or days of the event. Bolstering a country\'s preparedness and local emergency response capacity is therefore essential in minimizing harm and casualty in the wake of a natural disaster. The United Nations International Strategy for Disaster Reduction (UNISDR) is the chief international agency responsible for coordinating and advocating disaster reduction efforts throughout the world. Its programs aim to reduce the destruction, injury, and loss of life that occur due to natural disasters. Its programs are primarily directed by the Hyogo Framework for Action, a 10-year plan adopted by the United Nations in 2005 to make the world safer from natural hazards. The plan\'s specific strategies for risk reduction include:\r\n\r\n Comprehensive risk assessment of potential natural hazards within a country\r\nCreation of early warning systems\r\nDevelopment of scientific capacity to forecast disasters\r\nPublic education and awareness of disaster risks\r\nIncrease the resilience of public facilities crucial to disaster response (hospitals, schools)\r\nIncorporation of risk assessments in urban planning\r\nSetting aside emergency funds for disaster response\r\n\r\nIn addition to the UN\'s efforts, the World Bank established the Global Facility for Disaster Reduction and Recovery (GFDRR) to help fund development projects that enhance local capacities for disaster prevention and emergency preparedness in developing countries. In addition to its emergency response activities, humanitarian aid organization Oxfam also carries out disaster reduction programs that help communities perform assessments and forecasting and to prepare for known risks. Disaster response Disaster response encompasses the full range of humanitarian aid-delivery of food and water, shelter, medical services, search and rescue, counseling-and is performed by an assortment of international agencies and organizations. Within the UN there exist multiple organizations that perform disaster response activities in different capacities - the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), UNICEF, World Food Programme, World Health Organization, and United Nations Development Programme. Among non-governmental organizations, the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent societies is the most extensive and well-known emergency response and relief entity worldwide. Other major international organizations include Oxfam International, Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders), and CARE. The United States Agency for International Development is the U.S. government agency tasked with providing disaster assistance in other countries. Today, the chief challenge for the community of humanitarian and disaster relief organizations and agencies - besides funding and resources - is that of coordination. As a result of having different protocols, priorities, and information systems, collaboration among organizations and agencies in the event of an international crisis is often difficult, resulting in inefficient use of resources and information sharing. Recent developments In 2006, the UN\'s OCHA, which plays the central coordinating role among government agencies and NGO\'s worldwide, instituted \"the Cluster approach\" as a UN humanitarian reform. Partly as a response to the Indian Ocean Earthquake and Tsunami of 2004, the new organizational strategy seeks to increase the effectiveness of international disaster response by enhancing partnerships between the UN, the Red Cross Movement, and NGOs. In 2008, the World Health organization reported that the system\'s deployment in the wake of the catastrophic Cyclone Nargis in Burma marked a turning point in disaster response.','<p>Improving disaster response in developing countries relies on a combination of deploying effective international aid while also helping countries themselves become more resilient and less vulnerable to disaster.<br /><br /> <em>Disaster reduction</em><br /><br /> In most disasters, the majority of lives are lost within the first few hours or days of the event. Bolstering a country\'s preparedness and local emergency response capacity is therefore essential in minimizing harm and casualty in the wake of a natural disaster.<br /><br /> The United Nations International Strategy for Disaster Reduction (UNISDR) is the chief international agency responsible for coordinating and advocating disaster reduction efforts throughout the world. Its programs aim to reduce the destruction, injury, and loss of life that occur due to natural disasters. Its programs are primarily directed by the Hyogo Framework for Action, a 10-year plan adopted by the United Nations in 2005 to make the world safer from natural hazards. The plan\'s specific strategies for risk reduction include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> Comprehensive risk assessment of potential natural hazards within a country</li>\r\n<li>Creation of early warning systems</li>\r\n<li>Development of scientific capacity to forecast disasters</li>\r\n<li>Public education and awareness of disaster risks</li>\r\n<li>Increase the resilience of public facilities crucial to disaster response (hospitals, schools)</li>\r\n<li>Incorporation of risk assessments in urban planning</li>\r\n<li>Setting aside emergency funds for disaster response</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In addition to the UN\'s efforts, the World Bank established the Global Facility for Disaster Reduction and Recovery (GFDRR) to help fund development projects that enhance local capacities for disaster prevention and emergency preparedness in developing countries.<br /><br /> In addition to its emergency response activities, humanitarian aid organization Oxfam also carries out disaster reduction programs that help communities perform assessments and forecasting and to prepare for known risks.<br /><br /> <em>Disaster response</em><br /><br /> Disaster response encompasses the full range of humanitarian aid-delivery of food and water, shelter, medical services, search and rescue, counseling-and is performed by an assortment of international agencies and organizations.<br /><br /> Within the UN there exist multiple organizations that perform disaster response activities in different capacities - the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), UNICEF, World Food Programme, World Health Organization, and United Nations Development Programme.<br /><br /> Among non-governmental organizations, the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent societies is the most extensive and well-known emergency response and relief entity worldwide.<br /><br /> Other major international organizations include Oxfam International, Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders), and CARE. The United States Agency for International Development is the U.S. government agency tasked with providing disaster assistance in other countries.<br /><br /> Today, the chief challenge for the community of humanitarian and disaster relief organizations and agencies - besides funding and resources - is that of coordination. As a result of having different protocols, priorities, and information systems, collaboration among organizations and agencies in the event of an international crisis is often difficult, resulting in inefficient use of resources and information sharing.<br /><br /> <em>Recent developments</em><br /><br /> In 2006, the UN\'s OCHA, which plays the central coordinating role among government agencies and NGO\'s worldwide, instituted \"the Cluster approach\" as a UN humanitarian reform. Partly as a response to the Indian Ocean Earthquake and Tsunami of 2004, the new organizational strategy seeks to increase the effectiveness of international disaster response by enhancing partnerships between the UN, the Red Cross Movement, and NGOs.<br /><br /> In 2008, the World Health organization reported that the system\'s deployment in the wake of the catastrophic Cyclone Nargis in Burma marked a turning point in disaster response.</p>'),(28688,178,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nUN Global Issues: Humanitarian and Disaster Relief Assistance\r\nRootcause: International Disaster Response\r\nUNISDR: The Hyogo Framework\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nProfile Photo Source: Oxfam','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.un.org/en/globalissues/humanitarian/\">UN Global Issues: Humanitarian and Disaster Relief Assistance</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.rootcause.org/research/international_disaster_response\">Rootcause: International Disaster Response</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.unisdr.org/we/coordinate/hfa\">UNISDR: The Hyogo Framework</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Profile Photo Source: Oxfam</em></p>'),(28689,245,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','Despite gains in the legal protection of gender equality under U.S. law and decades of shifts in cultural mores regarding women&rsquo;s sexuality, ability, and intelligence, women in the U.S. still face inequality and prejudice in the workplace, within family life, and even in courts of law. Some of the biggest challenges for American women today include workplace discrimination, access to reproductive health, and sexual violence.&nbsp; Workplace Discrimination The Equal Pay Act of 1963 outlawed the practice of sex-based wage discrimination, after which employers were no longer able to promote or base pay on gender. Two years later, President Eisenhower formed the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, which has since served a vital role in passing legislation to end workplace discrimination, including sex-selective advertising and discrimination against pregnant employees. Women today constitute roughly half of the workforce and are equal, if not primary, breadwinners in four out of ten families.But sex-based wage gaps and institutionalized attitudes that devalue women&rsquo;s contributions to the workforce still persist. When the Equal Pay Act was passed, women were making an average of 59 cents for every dollar paid to men. In 2009, women&rsquo;s median annual paychecks showed a wage discrepancy of 77 cents for every dollar paid to men. This means, on average, the wage gap has closed less than half a penny per year since 1963.In addition, jobs with higher percentages of female workers often pay less than jobs with lower percentages of female workers, regardless of the education levels needed to attain those positions. The Bureau of Labor Statistics reports that Police and Sheriff Patrol Officers, only an estimated 13% of which are female, make a mean annual wage of $55,620. In the predominantly female-staffed Home Health Aid field however, workers can expect a mean annual wage of $21,760.Reproductive RightsThe issue of reproductive rights has long been a cornerstone of the U.S. feminist movement. Reproductive rights include access to quality sexual and reproductive health care and the ability to freely make reproduction-related decisions. It includes issues like birth control and education about contraception and sexually transmitted diseases.A woman&rsquo;s right to abortion has been one of the most contested issues within women&rsquo;s rights.&nbsp; In 1973 the Supreme Court case, Roe v. Wade, dictated that a woman&rsquo;s decision to obtain a therapeutic abortion should be protected under the law. Since 1973, there have been numerous state and federal pushes to repeal this right, as well as proposals to remove federal funding from health care providers that offer abortion services. &nbsp;Some consider these bills to be a direct attack on providers like Planned Parenthood, a nation-wide health care provider operating more than 800 health centers across the U.S. and serving 3 million men and women a year.Rape and Sexual Assault1 out of every 6 American women has been the victim of an attempted or completed rape in her lifetime.&nbsp; But despite the high prevalence of rape and sexual assault in the U.S., and factoring in high instances of unreported rapes (estimates indicate less than half of all cases are reported), the Rape, Abuse and Incest National Network notes that only 6% of rapists will ever spend a day in jail.Low instances of reporting can be contributed to stigma and cultural mores that punish women for taking action against their attackers. Victim blaming is when a sexual assault survivor is accused, by virtue of their dress, attitude, job, alcohol consumption, and numerous other factors, to have invited or instigated the events that led to their sexual assault. In court cases victim blaming is also used to insinuate that the victim is unable to provide accurate testimony.In addition, in the United States two-thirds of all rape victims and 93% of juvenile rape victims know their attacker, increasing the likelihood of emotional and psychological force and date rape.\r\n&nbsp;','<p>Despite gains in the legal protection of gender equality under U.S. law and decades of shifts in cultural mores regarding women&rsquo;s sexuality, ability, and intelligence, women in the U.S. still face inequality and prejudice in the workplace, within family life, and even in courts of law. Some of the biggest challenges for American women today include workplace discrimination, access to reproductive health, and sexual violence.&nbsp;<br /><br /> <em>Workplace Discrimination<br /></em> The Equal Pay Act of 1963 outlawed the practice of sex-based wage discrimination, after which employers were no longer able to promote or base pay on gender. Two years later, President Eisenhower formed the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, which has since served a vital role in passing legislation to end workplace discrimination, including sex-selective advertising and discrimination against pregnant employees. Women today constitute roughly half of the workforce and are equal, if not primary, breadwinners in four out of ten families.<br /><br />But sex-based wage gaps and institutionalized attitudes that devalue women&rsquo;s contributions to the workforce still persist. When the Equal Pay Act was passed, women were making an average of 59 cents for every dollar paid to men. In 2009, women&rsquo;s median annual paychecks showed a wage discrepancy of 77 cents for every dollar paid to men. This means, on average, the wage gap has closed less than half a penny per year since 1963.<br /><br />In addition, jobs with higher percentages of female workers often pay less than jobs with lower percentages of female workers, regardless of the education levels needed to attain those positions. The Bureau of Labor Statistics reports that Police and Sheriff Patrol Officers, only an estimated 13% of which are female, make a mean annual wage of $55,620. In the predominantly female-staffed Home Health Aid field however, workers can expect a mean annual wage of $21,760.<br /><br /><em>Reproductive Rights<br /></em>The issue of reproductive rights has long been a cornerstone of the U.S. feminist movement. Reproductive rights include access to quality sexual and reproductive health care and the ability to freely make reproduction-related decisions. It includes issues like birth control and education about contraception and sexually transmitted diseases.<br /><br />A woman&rsquo;s right to abortion has been one of the most contested issues within women&rsquo;s rights.&nbsp; In 1973 the Supreme Court case, <em>Roe v. Wade</em>, dictated that a woman&rsquo;s decision to obtain a therapeutic abortion should be protected under the law. Since 1973, there have been numerous state and federal pushes to repeal this right, as well as proposals to remove federal funding from health care providers that offer abortion services. &nbsp;Some consider these bills to be a direct attack on providers like <a href=\"/plannedparenthoodfederationofamerica\">Planned Parenthood</a>, a nation-wide health care provider operating more than 800 health centers across the U.S. and serving 3 million men and women a year.<br /><br /><em>Rape and Sexual Assault<br /></em>1 out of every 6 American women has been the victim of an attempted or completed rape in her lifetime.&nbsp; But despite the high prevalence of rape and sexual assault in the U.S., and factoring in high instances of unreported rapes (estimates indicate less than half of all cases are reported), the Rape, Abuse and Incest National Network notes that only 6% of rapists will ever spend a day in jail.<br /><br />Low instances of reporting can be contributed to stigma and cultural mores that punish women for taking action against their attackers. Victim blaming is when a sexual assault survivor is accused, by virtue of their dress, attitude, job, alcohol consumption, and numerous other factors, to have invited or instigated the events that led to their sexual assault. In court cases victim blaming is also used to insinuate that the victim is unable to provide accurate testimony.<br /><br />In addition, in the United States two-thirds of all rape victims and 93% of juvenile rape victims know their attacker, increasing the likelihood of emotional and psychological force and date rape.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),(28691,245,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Organizations and agencies working to improve the condition of women throughout the United States work in a number of capacities and causes:\r\n\r\nAdvocacy: &nbsp;Organizations like the National Organization for Women mobilize feminist activists to organize rallies and protests, support laws that promote equality for women, and support new feminist voters and candidates.\r\nEducation and awareness:&nbsp; Educating women, especially college-aged women, about the realities of sexual assault in the U.S. today is vital in order to decrease instances of rape. The Rape, Abuse, &amp; Incest National Network is the nation&rsquo;s largest anti-sexual violence organization and works to educate the public, prevent sexual violence, improve service to assault victims, and ensure that rapists are brought to justice.\r\nReproductive rights and services: &nbsp;Organizations like Planned Parenthood fight to provide quality and comprehensive reproductive care for women.\r\nMentoring: Several organizations work to mentor at-risk youth and survivors of sexual trafficking, including the Young Womens Leadership Network and Girls Education and Mentoring Service (GEMS).\r\n','<p>Organizations and agencies working to improve the condition of women throughout the United States work in a number of capacities and causes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Advocacy: &nbsp;</strong>Organizations like the <a href=\"http://www.now.org/actions/\">National Organization for Women</a> mobilize feminist activists to organize rallies and protests, support laws that promote equality for women, and support new feminist voters and candidates.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Education and awareness:&nbsp; </strong>Educating women, especially college-aged women, about the realities of sexual assault in the U.S. today is vital in order to decrease instances of rape. The <a href=\"http://www.rainn.org/get-involved\">Rape, Abuse, &amp; Incest National Network</a> is the nation&rsquo;s largest anti-sexual violence organization and works to educate the public, prevent sexual violence, improve service to assault victims, and ensure that rapists are brought to justice.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Reproductive rights and services: &nbsp;</strong>Organizations like <a href=\"http://www.plannedparenthood.org/get-involved/index.htm\">Planned Parenthood</a> fight to provide quality and comprehensive reproductive care for women.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Mentoring: </strong>Several organizations work to mentor <a href=\"/ywln\">at-risk youth</a> and survivors of <a href=\"/gems\">sexual trafficking</a>, including the Young Womens Leadership Network and Girls Education and Mentoring Service (GEMS).</li>\r\n</ul>'),(28694,203,21,'center',0,'What is the problem?','At present, three quarters of the world\'s poor get their food and make their living from farming small plots of land. According to the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation, agricultural development in the developing world is two to four times more effective at reducing hunger and poverty than any other method. Successful family farms can feed families, send children to school, transform local economies and revitalize communities and regions. Family farms in developing countries, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia, suffer from multiple challenges:\r\n\r\nLack of quality seeds and fertilizer\r\nDegraded soil\r\nDepleted and polluted water\r\nResilient pests and crop disease\r\nLack of irrigation and other farming technologies\r\nLack of access to markets for their crops\r\n\r\nMany believe that addressing these challenges holds the same promise as the \"Green Revolution\" that occurred between 1960 and 1990, when a massive transfer of agricultural technology and practices to Asia and Latin America resulted in hundreds of millions of lives saved by boosting crop yields and increasing food security.\r\nIt is important to note, however, that the regions that today\'s efforts focus on-primarily sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia-face a different set of social, political, and economic challenges, including lack of infrastructure, corruption, and lack of water for irrigation. And while the Green Revolution did have a significant effect on large-scale food security and hunger trends, it lacked the specific focus on improving the viability and economic conditions of small farmers that today\'s efforts have.','<p>At present, three quarters of the world\'s poor get their food and make their living from farming small plots of land. According to the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation, agricultural development in the developing world is two to four times more effective at reducing hunger and poverty than any other method. Successful family farms can feed families, send children to school, transform local economies and revitalize communities and regions.<br /><br /> Family farms in developing countries, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia, suffer from multiple challenges:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lack of quality seeds and fertilizer</li>\r\n<li>Degraded soil</li>\r\n<li>Depleted and polluted water</li>\r\n<li>Resilient pests and crop disease</li>\r\n<li>Lack of irrigation and other farming technologies</li>\r\n<li>Lack of access to markets for their crops</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Many believe that addressing these challenges holds the same promise as the \"Green Revolution\" that occurred between 1960 and 1990, when a massive transfer of agricultural technology and practices to Asia and Latin America resulted in hundreds of millions of lives saved by boosting crop yields and increasing food security.</p>\r\n<p>It is important to note, however, that the regions that today\'s efforts focus on-primarily sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia-face a different set of social, political, and economic challenges, including lack of infrastructure, corruption, and lack of water for irrigation. And while the Green Revolution did have a significant effect on large-scale food security and hunger trends, it lacked the specific focus on improving the viability and economic conditions of small farmers that today\'s efforts have.</p>'),(28695,245,21,'center',2,'Further Reading','\r\nRape, Incest, and Abuse National Network: Sexual Violence Information\r\nACLU:Women&rsquo;s Rights page&nbsp;\r\nUS Department of Labor:Women&rsquo;s Statistics page\r\n\r\nProfile Photo Source: Planned Parenthood Federation of America','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.rainn.org/get-information\">Rape, Incest, and Abuse National Network: Sexual Violence Information</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aclu.org/womens-rights\">ACLU:Women&rsquo;s Rights page&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.dol.gov/wb/stats/main.htm\">US Department of Labor:Women&rsquo;s Statistics page</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br /><em>Profile Photo Source: Planned Parenthood Federation of America</em>'),(28696,203,21,'center',1,'How is the problem being addressed?','Sustainable agriculture within the context of development aims to marry the principles and technologies of sustainability with the objective of raising the economic opportunities of small farmers throughout the developing world.\r\nSustainable agriculture is a direct response to the practice of using intensive, ever-growing amounts of water, pesticides, fertilizers and energy that characterized the agricultural advances of the Green Revolution. Sustainable practices seek to preserve resources and minimize waste in a number of ways:\r\n\r\nPreserving soil fertility through minimal plowing\r\nRecycling crop waste\r\nAvoidance of pesticide overuse through crop rotation, diversification, and integrated pest management\r\nTargeted fertilizer use\r\nPrecision irrigation technologies\r\nUse of high quality seeds\r\n\r\nThe promise of these sustainable techniques is in their ability to preserve resources in areas and populations where such resources are scarce to begin with.\r\nAlong with improvements to farming practices and crop yields, agricultural development must also focus on improving small farmers\' access to markets where they can sell surplus crops and build livelihoods. Accomplishing this goal involves:\r\n\r\nConnecting rural areas to larger urban areas through better roads\r\nProviding safe, reliable, low-cost transportation methods for crops\r\nCreating reliable buyers of crops in order to make production less risky for farmers\r\n\r\nThese various goals are pursued by a number of government agencies, multilateral organizations and foundations. The Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation\'s Agricultural Development program invests heavily in small family farms throughout sub-Saharan Africa. The U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) funds and oversees various sustainable agriculture development programs throughout the developing world.\r\nThe Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations plays a significant international coordinating and advisory role by establishing and disseminating standard practices of sustainability throughout the developing world. In 2011, the agency published Save and Grow: A policymaker\'s guide to the sustainable intensification of smallholder crop production. The International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) is a specialized agency within the United Nations dedicated to lifting rural people in developing countries out of poverty through agricultural development.\r\nWhile primarily engaged in food aid, the UN World Food Programme\'s Purchase for Progress program aims to help small farmers access markets and grow their businesses by buying its food aid from these farmers, providing them with a steady and reliable buyer of surplus crops.\r\nSmaller NGOs like One Acre Fund help subsistence farmers by providing seeds and fertilizer, education, and market access.','<p>Sustainable agriculture within the context of development aims to marry the principles and technologies of sustainability with the objective of raising the economic opportunities of small farmers throughout the developing world.</p>\r\n<p>Sustainable agriculture is a direct response to the practice of using intensive, ever-growing amounts of water, pesticides, fertilizers and energy that characterized the agricultural advances of the Green Revolution. Sustainable practices seek to preserve resources and minimize waste in a number of ways:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preserving soil fertility through minimal plowing</li>\r\n<li>Recycling crop waste</li>\r\n<li>Avoidance of pesticide overuse through crop rotation, diversification, and integrated pest management</li>\r\n<li>Targeted fertilizer use</li>\r\n<li>Precision irrigation technologies</li>\r\n<li>Use of high quality seeds</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The promise of these sustainable techniques is in their ability to preserve resources in areas and populations where such resources are scarce to begin with.</p>\r\n<p>Along with improvements to farming practices and crop yields, agricultural development must also focus on improving small farmers\' access to markets where they can sell surplus crops and build livelihoods. Accomplishing this goal involves:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Connecting rural areas to larger urban areas through better roads</li>\r\n<li>Providing safe, reliable, low-cost transportation methods for crops</li>\r\n<li>Creating reliable buyers of crops in order to make production less risky for farmers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These various goals are pursued by a number of government agencies, multilateral organizations and foundations. The Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation\'s Agricultural Development program invests heavily in small family farms throughout sub-Saharan Africa. The U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) funds and oversees various sustainable agriculture development programs throughout the developing world.</p>\r\n<p>The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations plays a significant international coordinating and advisory role by establishing and disseminating standard practices of sustainability throughout the developing world. In 2011, the agency published <a href=\"http://www.fao.org/ag/save-and-grow/\"><em>Save and Grow: A policymaker\'s guide to the sustainable intensification of smallholder crop production</em></a>.<br /><br /> The International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) is a specialized agency within the United Nations dedicated to lifting rural people in developing countries out of poverty through agricultural development.</p>\r\n<p>While primarily engaged in food aid, the UN World Food Programme\'s Purchase for Progress program aims to help small farmers access markets and grow their businesses by buying its food aid from these farmers, providing them with a steady and reliable buyer of surplus crops.</p>\r\n<p>Smaller NGOs like <a href=\"/oneacrefund\">One Acre Fund</a> help subsistence farmers by providing seeds and fertilizer, education, and market access.</p>'),(28697,245,21,'left',0,'Statistics','       Normal 0     false false false  EN-US JA X-NONE                                                                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\nEvery 2 minutes, someone in the U.S. is sexually assaulted.\r\n15 of 16 rapists will never spend a day in jail.\r\nIn 2009, the U.S. Census Bureau reported that female full time year-round workers earned 23% less than similar male workers.\r\nWomen earn 57% of all bachelor&rsquo;s degrees and represent 57% of all college enrollment.\r\nOnly 15 Fortune 500 Companies are run by women.\r\nAn estimated 11% of U.S. public companies have women on the board of directors.\r\n','<p><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <o:OfficeDocumentSettings> <o:AllowPNG /> </o:OfficeDocumentSettings> </xml><![endif]--> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:WordDocument> <w:View>Normal</w:View> <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom> <w:TrackMoves /> <w:TrackFormatting /> <w:PunctuationKerning /> <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas /> <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid> <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent> <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText> <w:DoNotPromoteQF /> <w:LidThemeOther>EN-US</w:LidThemeOther> <w:LidThemeAsian>JA</w:LidThemeAsian> <w:LidThemeComplexScript>X-NONE</w:LidThemeComplexScript> <w:Compatibility> <w:BreakWrappedTables /> <w:SnapToGridInCell /> <w:WrapTextWithPunct /> <w:UseAsianBreakRules /> <w:DontGrowAutofit /> <w:SplitPgBreakAndParaMark /> <w:EnableOpenTypeKerning /> <w:DontFlipMirrorIndents /> <w:OverrideTableStyleHps /> <w:UseFELayout /> </w:Compatibility> <m:mathPr> <m:mathFont m:val=\"Cambria Math\" /> <m:brkBin m:val=\"before\" /> <m:brkBinSub m:val=\"&#45;-\" /> <m:smallFrac m:val=\"off\" /> <m:dispDef /> <m:lMargin m:val=\"0\" /> <m:rMargin m:val=\"0\" /> <m:defJc m:val=\"centerGroup\" /> <m:wrapIndent m:val=\"1440\" /> <m:intLim m:val=\"subSup\" /> <m:naryLim m:val=\"undOvr\" /> </m:mathPr></w:WordDocument> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:LatentStyles DefLockedState=\"false\" DefUnhideWhenUsed=\"true\"   DefSemiHidden=\"true\" DefQFormat=\"false\" DefPriority=\"99\"   LatentStyleCount=\"276\"> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"0\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Normal\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 1\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 2\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 3\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 4\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 5\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 7\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 8\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"9\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"heading 9\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 1\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 2\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 3\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 4\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 5\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 7\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 8\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" Name=\"toc 9\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"35\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"caption\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"10\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Title\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"1\" Name=\"Default Paragraph Font\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"11\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtitle\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"22\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Strong\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"fals